{"title_page": "List of shopping malls in Toronto", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:YorkdaleShoppingCentre6.jpg|thumb|Opened in 1964, [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] was the first enclosed, automobile-centred shopping mall opened in Toronto.]]\nThe following is a '''list of shopping malls in Toronto''', Ontario, Canada. The first enclosed shopping mall in [[Toronto]] was the Toronto Arcade in [[Downtown Toronto|the downtown core]]. The first shopping mall of the enclosed, automobile-centred design type was [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]], opened in 1964. For shopping malls [[Area code 905|surrounding the city of Toronto]], please see the template at the bottom of this article.\n\n==Major shopping centres==\nThese shopping centres each have over a hundred stores and are anchored by multiple department stores. They are also the five largest malls in Toronto. Each provides thousands of automobile parking spaces. With the exception of [[Sherway Gardens]], all of these malls have direct pedestrian connections with the [[Toronto subway]] system, though Sherway Gardens has bus connections through the [[Toronto Transit Commission]]'s [[Toronto Transit Commission bus system|bus network]] and [[MiWay]] of [[Mississauga]]. Yorkdale is Toronto's first major shopping centre and was the world's largest when it was first opened. The Toronto Eaton Centre is the most visited shopping mall in North America, given its downtown location and direct access to two subway stations. These five malls were completed within a 13-year span. A sixth major mall, East Harbour, is planned for Toronto's east end by the interchange of [[Don Valley Parkway]] and Gardiner Expressway/[[Lake Shore Boulevard|Lake Shore Boulevard East]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eastharbour.ca|title=East Harbour {{!}} Toronto, Ontario, Canada|website=eastharbour.ca|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n[[File:Eatoncentrertorontohall.JPG|right|thumb|With over {{convert|159979|sqm|sqft}} of retail space, [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] is the second largest shopping centre in Toronto, and the [[List of largest shopping malls in Canada|fifth largest in Canada]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name \n! District\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Major intersection \n! class=\"unsortable\" | [[Toronto subway|Direct subway connection]]\n! Developer/operator\n! Retail space\n! Year opened\n|-\n\n| [[Fairview Mall]] || [[North York]] || [[Don Mills Road]]\u2014[[Sheppard Avenue]] || [[Don Mills station|Don Mills]] || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|81874|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1970\n|-\n| [[Scarborough Town Centre]] || [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]] || [[McCowan Road (Toronto)|McCowan Road]]\u2014[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] || [[Scarborough Centre station|Scarborough Centre]] || [[Oxford Properties]] || {{convert|121467|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1973\n|-\n| [[Sherway Gardens]] || [[Etobicoke]] || [[The Queensway]]\u2014[[The West Mall]] ||  || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|109800|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1971\n|-\n| [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] || [[Old Toronto]] || [[Yonge Street]]\u2014[[Dundas Street]]<br />[[Yonge Street]]\u2014[[Queen Street (Toronto)|Queen Street]] || [[Dundas station (Toronto)|Dundas]]<br />[[Queen station|Queen]] || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|159979|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1977\n|-\n| [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] || [[North York]] || [[Allen Road]]\u2014[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] || [[Yorkdale station|Yorkdale]] || [[Oxford Properties]] || {{convert|171473|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1964\n|}\n\n==District or neighbourhood shopping centres==\nThe district or neighbourhood level of shopping centres in Toronto are typically built around one or a few department stores or grocery supermarkets and are enclosed. These shopping centres typically provide a surrounding free parking lot. Most of these are located in the former suburbs of Toronto, where land was available for parking. There are only three shopping malls of this type within [[Old Toronto|Toronto's pre-1998 city limits]]: Galleria Shopping Centre (at Dufferin Street and Dupont Street), Dufferin Mall (on Dufferin Street south of Bloor Street and north of College Street), and Gerrard Square (on Gerrard Street East east of Pape Avenue). There are a few ethnic malls of this type as well.\n[[File:Bayview Village Shopping Centre.jpg|thumb|[[Bayview Village Shopping Centre]] is a shopping centre built in suburban Toronto, built between [[Bayview Village]] and [[Willowdale, Toronto|Willowdale]] neighbourhoods.]]\n[[File:Splendid China Tower.JPG|thumb|[[Splendid China Mall]] is a Chinese-themed ethnic shopping centre located in the [[Milliken, Ontario|Milliken]] neighbourhood. The mall is across [[Steeles Avenue]] from [[Pacific Mall]] in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]]<!--Don't get too detailed about Pacific Mall in this article-->.]]\n<!--This section is for shopping malls-->\n* [[Agincourt Mall]] (Kennedy Road and Sheppard Avenue East), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Albion Centre (Finch Avenue West and Kipling Avenue), [[Etobicoke]]\n* [[Bayview Village Shopping Centre|Bayview Village]] (Bayview Avenue and Sheppard Avenue East), [[North York]]\n* [[Bridlewood Mall]] (Warden Avenue and Finch Avenue East), Scarborough\n* [[Cedarbrae Mall]] (Lawrence Avenue East and Markham Road), Scarborough\n* [[Centerpoint Mall (Toronto)|Centerpoint Mall]] (Yonge Street and Steeles Avenue West), North York\n* [[Cloverdale Mall]] (Dundas Street West and The East Mall), Etobicoke\n* [[Dufferin Mall]] (Dufferin Street, south of Bloor Street West), [[Old Toronto]]\n* [[East York Town Centre]] (Millwood Road and Overlea Boulevard), [[East York]]\n* [[Eglinton Square Shopping Centre]] (Eglinton Avenue East and Victoria Park Avenue), Scarborough\n* Jane-Finch Mall ([[Jane and Finch]])), North York\n* [[Lawrence Allen Centre]] (formerly Lawrence Square Shopping Centre; renamed in late 2019) (Allen Road and Lawrence Avenue West), North York\n* Malvern Town Centre (Neilson Road and Tapscott Road), Scarborough\n* North York Sheridan Mall (Jane Street and Wilson Avenue), North York\n* [[Parkway Mall]] (Victoria Park Avenue and Ellesmere Road), Scarborough\n* [[Woodbine Centre]] (Rexdale Boulevard and Highway 27), Etobicoke\n* [[Woodside Square]] (McCowan Road and Finch Avenue East), Scarborough\n\nEthnic malls\n* [[Splendid China Mall]] (Steeles Avenue east of Kennedy Road), Scarborough; converted from [[Canadian Tire]]\n<!--This section is for shopping malls-->\n\n==Malls located within major office buildings==\n[[File:College Park December 2009.jpg|thumb|[[College Park (Toronto)|College Park]] is one of several buildings in Toronto that is used as an office complex and a shopping centre.]]\nOne configuration of shopping mall in Toronto is the self-contained type located within a commercial office building, sometimes around a central atrium. This type typically does not provide a surrounding parking lot. These malls typically house from a dozen to several dozen stores. Most of these are connected to a station of the [[Toronto subway]] system. In the case of the Hudson's Bay Centre, the mall connects the department store to the Toronto subway system at [[Bloor\u2013Yonge station]]. These malls are located in the core ([[Old Toronto]]), unless marked otherwise:\n* The [[Atrium on Bay]] (Dundas Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Canada Square Complex|Canada Square]] ([[Yonge-Eglinton|Yonge Street and Eglinton Avenue West]])\n* Chinatown Centre ([[Chinatown, Toronto|Chinatown]]); ethnic mall\n* [[College Park (Toronto)|College Park]] (Yonge Street and College Street)\n* [[The Crossways, Toronto|The Crossways]] (Bloor Street West and Dundas Street West)\n* Cumberland Terrace (Bay Street and Bloor Street West)\n* Dragon City ([[Chinatown, Toronto|Chinatown]]) (Dundas Street West and Spadina Avenue); ethnic mall\n* Dynasty Centre (Sheppard Avenue East and Midland Avenue), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]; ethnic mall\n* [[Empress Walk]] (Empress Avenue and Yonge Street), [[North York]]\n* Holt Renfrew Centre (Bloor Street West and Bay Street)\n* [[Hudson's Bay Centre]] (Bloor Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Manulife Centre]] (Bloor Street West and Bay Street)\n* [[Queens Quay (Toronto)|Queen's Quay]] Terminal (Queen's Quay West and York Street)\n* Sheppard Centre  (Sheppard Avenue East and Yonge Street), [[North York]]\n* Yonge Eglinton Centre ([[Yonge-Eglinton|Yonge Street and Eglinton Avenue West]])\n* [[Yorkville Village]] (formerly Hazelton Lanes) (Avenue Road and Yorkville Avenue)\n* [[York Mills Centre]] (York Mills Road and Yonge Street), North York\n\n===PATH underground shopping complex===\n[[File:Toronto PATH (15126928816).jpg|thumb|Signage for the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] from [[Scotia Plaza]]. The PATH connects most of [[Downtown Toronto|downtown]] and is the world's largest [[Underground city|underground shopping complex]].]]\nIn [[Downtown Toronto]], primarily in the [[Financial District, Toronto|Financial District]], there are interconnected shopping malls located one flight of stairs underground. The complex as a whole is named '[[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]]'. The Toronto Eaton Centre (see above) is connected to the complex. The complex has 1,200 stores, and according to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', the PATH is the largest [[Underground city|underground shopping complex]] in the world with {{Convert|371600|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.ca/explore-enjoy/visitor-services/path-torontos-downtown-pedestrian-walkway/|title=PATH \u2013 Toronto's Downtown Pedestrian Walkway|date=15 August 2017|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n* [[Brookfield Place (Toronto)|Brookfield Place]] (bounded by Front Street West, Bay Street, Wellington Street West, and Yonge Street)\n* [[Commerce Court]] (Yonge Street and King Street West)\n* [[First Canadian Place]] (Bay Street and King Street West)\n* [[Metro Hall]] (John Street and King Street West)\n* [[Royal Bank Plaza]] (Bay Street and Front Street West)\n* [[Scotia Plaza]] (King Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Toronto-Dominion Centre]] (bounded by King Street West, Bay Street, Wellington Street West, and York Street)\n* [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] (Bay Street and Front Street West)\n\n==Open-air shopping plazas==\nOpen-air shopping plazas are larger collections of stores built with surrounding parking areas, with parking spaces separated from the storefronts by sidewalks. These shopping centres generally serve the local surrounding area and have a large proportion of family-run businesses, some of which are ethnic.\n[[File:Shops at Don Mills (37496324736).jpg|thumb|[[Shops at Don Mills]] is one of several open-air malls in Toronto.]]\n* Chartwell Plaza (Brimley Road and Huntingwood Drive), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Dragon Centre (Sheppard Avenue East and Glen Watford Drive), Scarborough; ethnic mall\n* Dufferin & Steeles Plaza [[North York]]\n* Dufferin Business Centre (Dufferin Street between Castlefield Avenue and the former [[York, Toronto|York]]-[[North York]] boundary), [[York, Toronto|York]]\n* Iranian Plaza (Yonge Street between Cummer Avenue and Steeles Avenue), North York; ethnic mall\n* Lawrence Plaza (Bathurst Street and Lawrence Avenue West), North York\n* Peanut Plaza (Don Mills Road and Van Horne Avenue), North York\n* Sheppard Plaza (Sheppard Avenue West and Bathurst Street), North York\n* [[Shops at Don Mills]] (Don Mills Road and Lawrence Avenue East), North York\n* Sunnybrook Plaza (Eglinton Avenue East and Bayview Avenue), [[East York]]\n* Tam O'Shanter Plaza (Sheppard Avenue East east of Kennedy Road), Scarborough\n* The Landmark (Steeles Avenue and Middlefield Road), Scarborough; ethnic mall\n* Victoria Terrace (Victoria Park Avenue and Lawrence Avenue East), North York\n* Whiteshield Plaza (Kennedy Road and Lawrence Avenue East), Scarborough\n* York Mills Gardens (Leslie Street and York Mills Road), North York\n\n==Power centres==\n[[Retail park|Power centres]] mainly consist of major national and international [[big-box store]]s with large amounts of parking space separate from the stores themselves, and which serve a larger area than the open-air shopping plazas do.\n[[File:Shoppers World Danforth.JPG|thumb|[[Shoppers World Danforth]] is an example of an early [[retail park|power centre]], one of several that can be found in the city.]]\n* Black Creek Super Value Centre (Rogers Road and Keele Street), [[York, Toronto|York]]\n* Crossroads (Weston Road and Highway 401), [[North York]]\n* Downsview Power Centre (unofficial name) (Dufferin Street and Wilson Avenue), North York\n* Dufferin and Steeles Power Centre (unofficial name) (Dufferin Street and Steeles Avenue), North York\n* [[Golden Mile, Toronto|Golden Mile]] (Eglinton Avenue East between Victoria Park Avenue and Birchmount Road), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Kennedy Commons (Kennedy Road and Highway 401), Scarborough\n* Leaside Centre (Eglinton Avenue East and Laird Drive), [[East York]]\n* [[Shoppers World Danforth]] (Danforth Avenue west of Victoria Park Avenue), East York\n* Queenswalk Centre (North Queen Street and Queensway), [[Etobicoke]]\n* Queensway Complex (Islington Avenue and Queensway), Etobicoke\n* [[Stock Yards Village]] (Keele Street/Weston Road and St. Clair Avenue West), [[Old Toronto]]\n\n==Flea markets==\nThe markets are housed indoors with stalls of independent vendors.\n* Downsview Park Merchant's Market, [[Downsview Park]] (Keele Street and Sheppard Avenue West), [[North York]]\n* Dr. Flea's, Highway 27 and Albion Road, [[Etobicoke]]\n* Jane Finch Flea Market, 1911 Finch Avenue West (Jane Street and Finch Avenue West), [[North York]]\n* Merchant's Flea Market, 1921 Eglinton Avenue East, (Warden Avenue and Eglinton Avenue East), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n\n==Former shopping malls==\nThe following shopping malls have been demolished or closed. Some have been replaced by new strip plazas or re-developed for non-retail uses:\n<!--Please limit the list to those within Toronto's city limits-->\n[[File:Yonge-arcade-interior-1885.jpg|thumb|The original [[Arcade Building (Toronto)|Yonge Street Arcade]] building, c. 1885. The shopping centre was opened in 1884 and operated until it was demolished in 1954.]]\n* The original [[Arcade Building (Toronto)#Original Arcade building|Yonge Street Arcade]] (1884\u20131954) at 137 Yonge Street and consisting of 52 stores was considered Canada's first indoor mall. It was demolished in 1954 following two fires and was replaced in 1960 by the [[Arcade Building (Toronto)|Arcade Building]], which had a similar [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] style concourse on its main floor until 2008 when the floor was redeveloped with the arcade being replaced with a fitness centre and offices.\n* [[Galleria Shopping Centre (Toronto)|Galleria Shopping Centre]] (Dufferin Street and Dupont Street), Old Toronto; set to close for redevelopment in early 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reimaginegalleria.com/project/|title=Project|website=Reimagine Galleria}}</ref>\n* [[Golden Mile, Toronto#Golden Mile Plaza|Golden Mile Plaza]] (1954\u20131986) at Eglinton Avenue East and Victoria Park Avenue, demolished after 1986 fire and later replaced with a power centre named Golden Mile Mall.\n* Morningside Mall (1979\u20132002) at Morningside Avenue and Kingston Road, [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]; the indoor mall<ref>http://www.felixkalmenson.com/files/gimgs/42_historicize-pdf.jpg{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=Johnny Au |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> was demolished to make way for an outdoor big box plaza called Morningside Crossing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westhillnews.blogspot.ca/2007/11/morningside-crossing.html|title=Morningside Crossing|website=westhillnews.blogspot.ca}}</ref>\n* Rexdale Plaza (1957\u20132004), Islington Avenue and Rexdale Boulevard, [[Etobicoke]]<ref>[http://www.uer.ca/locations/show.asp?locid=20545 Urban Exploration Resource]</ref> and enclosed in 1972. Most stores closed by 2003 and demolition of south end in 2004 with north end of mall retained (with an [[Asian supermarket]] and a few small stores). Since 2004, its south end was redeveloped as an outdoor mall with [[Walmart Canada|Wal-Mart]] Supercentre as a stand-alone big box store.\n* Warden Woods Mall or Warden Power Centre (1970\u20132005) at Warden Avenue north of St. Clair Avenue East near [[Warden station]], [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]<ref>[http://www.uer.ca/locations/show.asp?locid=23270 Urban Exploration Resource]</ref> was a full mall with three anchor stores (The Bay, Simpson's and a [[Knob Hill Farms]] grocery store) and later as clearance centre. It has since been demolished and replaced with townhouses.\n* Weston-Finch Mall (1960s\u20132006), Weston Road and Finch Avenue West, North York \u2014 former strip mall (with [[Zellers]], [[Canadian Tire]] and [[McDonald's Canada|McDonald's]] as tenants) and later as outlet facility; demolished 2006 and vacant lot{{when|date=August 2012}} awaiting redevelopment for rental apartments.\n*  Westside Mall, Eglinton Avenue West west of Caledonia Road, [[York, Toronto|York]] \u2014 replaced with a power centre of the same name during the early 2000s (with Canadian Tire, [[Rogers Plus]], [[FreshCo]] (renamed from Price Chopper), [[Dollar Tree Canada|Dollar Tree]] (formerly occupied by Shoppers Drug Mart) and [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]] as major tenants) and will be connected to [[Caledonia station]] of both GO Transit's [[Barrie line]] and the Toronto subway system in 2022.\n* [[Honeydale Mall]] (1973\u20132013): Located in [[Eatonville, Toronto|Eatonville]] neighbourhood of Toronto; officially closed on 28 June 2013.\n<!--Please limit the list to those within Toronto's city limits-->\n\n===Former flea markets===\n* Flea market at the southwest corner of Midland Avenue and Sheppard Avenue East is closed since the early 2000s and the property will be redeveloped concurrent with the [[Sheppard East LRT]]'s construction.\n* Dufferin and Steeles Flea Market, replaced with [[The Home Depot]].\n* Toronto Weston Flea Market, Old Weston Road and St. Clair Avenue West, [[Old Toronto]] (later relocated to a smaller site nearby on St. Clair Avenue West between Old Weston Road and GO Transit's Barrie Line)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[List of largest enclosed shopping malls in Canada]]\n* [[List of shopping malls in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Shopping Malls in the Golden Horseshoe}}\n{{Toronto}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Toronto| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of shopping malls|Toronto]]\n[[Category:Toronto-related lists|Shopping malls]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Ontario|shopping malls]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:YorkdaleShoppingCentre6.jpg|thumb|Opened in 1964, [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] was the first enclosed, automobile-centred shopping mall opened in Toronto.]]\nThe following is a '''list of shopping malls in Toronto''', Ontario, Canada. The first enclosed shopping mall in [[Toronto]] was the Toronto Arcade in [[Downtown Toronto|the downtown core]]. The first shopping mall of the enclosed, automobile-centred design type was [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]], opened in 1964. For shopping malls [[Area code 905|surrounding the city of Toronto]], please see the template at the bottom of this article.\n\n==Major shopping centres==\nThese shopping centres each have over a hundred stores and are anchored by multiple department stores. They are also the five largest malls in Toronto. Each provides thousands of automobile parking spaces. With the exception of [[Sherway Gardens]], all of these malls have direct pedestrian connections with the [[Toronto subway]] system, though Sherway Gardens has bus connections through the [[Toronto Transit Commission]]'s [[Toronto Transit Commission bus system|bus network]] and [[MiWay]] of [[Mississauga]]. Yorkdale is Toronto's first major shopping centre and was the world's largest when it was first opened. The Toronto Eaton Centre is the most visited shopping mall in North America, given its downtown location and direct access to two subway stations. These five malls were completed within a 13-year span. A sixth major mall, East Harbour, is planned for Toronto's east end by the interchange of [[Don Valley Parkway]] and Gardiner Expressway/[[Lake Shore Boulevard|Lake Shore Boulevard East]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eastharbour.ca|title=East Harbour {{!}} Toronto, Ontario, Canada|website=eastharbour.ca|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-08-28}}</ref>\n[[File:Eatoncentrertorontohall.JPG|right|thumb|With over {{convert|159979|sqm|sqft}} of retail space, [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] is the second largest shopping centre in Toronto, and the [[List of largest shopping malls in Canada|fifth largest in Canada]].]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name \n! District\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Major intersection \n! class=\"unsortable\" | [[Toronto subway|Direct subway connection]]\n! Developer/operator\n! Retail space\n! Year opened\n|-\n\n| [[Fairview Mall]] || [[North York]] || [[Don Mills Road]]\u2014[[Sheppard Avenue]] || [[Don Mills station|Don Mills]] || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|81874|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1970\n|-\n| [[Scarborough Town Centre]] || [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]] || [[McCowan Road (Toronto)|McCowan Road]]\u2014[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] || [[Scarborough Centre station|Scarborough Centre]] || [[Oxford Properties]] || {{convert|121467|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1973\n|-\n| [[Sherway Gardens]] || [[Etobicoke]] || [[The Queensway]]\u2014[[The West Mall]] ||  || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|109800|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1971\n|-\n| [[Toronto Eaton Centre]] || [[Old Toronto]] || [[Yonge Street]]\u2014[[Dundas Street]]<br />[[Yonge Street]]\u2014[[Queen Street (Toronto)|Queen Street]] || [[Dundas station (Toronto)|Dundas]]<br />[[Queen station|Queen]] || [[Cadillac Fairview]] || {{convert|159979|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1977\n|-\n| [[Yorkdale Shopping Centre]] || [[North York]] || [[Allen Road]]\u2014[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] || [[Yorkdale station|Yorkdale]] || [[Oxford Properties]] || {{convert|171473|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} || 1964\n|}\n\n==District or neighbourhood shopping centres==\nThe district or neighbourhood level of shopping centres in Toronto are typically built around one or a few department stores or grocery supermarkets and are enclosed. These shopping centres typically provide a surrounding free parking lot. Most of these are located in the former suburbs of Toronto, where land was available for parking. There are only three shopping malls of this type within [[Old Toronto|Toronto's pre-1998 city limits]]: Galleria Shopping Centre (at Dufferin Street and Dupont Street), Dufferin Mall (on Dufferin Street south of Bloor Street and north of College Street), and Gerrard Square (on Gerrard Street East east of Pape Avenue). There are a few ethnic malls of this type as well.\n[[File:Bayview Village Shopping Centre.jpg|thumb|[[Bayview Village Shopping Centre]] is a shopping centre built in suburban Toronto, built between [[Bayview Village]] and [[Willowdale, Toronto|Willowdale]] neighbourhoods.]]\n[[File:Splendid China Tower.JPG|thumb|[[Splendid China Mall]] is a Chinese-themed ethnic shopping centre located in the [[Milliken, Ontario|Milliken]] neighbourhood. The mall is across [[Steeles Avenue]] from [[Pacific Mall]] in [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]]<!--Don't get too detailed about Pacific Mall in this article-->.]]\n<!--This section is for shopping malls-->\n* [[Agincourt Mall]] (Kennedy Road and Sheppard Avenue East), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Albion Centre (Finch Avenue West and Kipling Avenue), [[Etobicoke]]\n* [[Bayview Village Shopping Centre|Bayview Village]] (Bayview Avenue and Sheppard Avenue East), [[North York]]\n* [[Bridlewood Mall]] (Warden Avenue and Finch Avenue East), Scarborough\n* [[Cedarbrae Mall]] (Lawrence Avenue East and Markham Road), Scarborough\n* [[Centerpoint Mall (Toronto)|Centerpoint Mall]] (Yonge Street and Steeles Avenue West), North York\n* [[Cloverdale Mall]] (Dundas Street West and The East Mall), Etobicoke\n* [[Dufferin Mall]] (Dufferin Street, south of Bloor Street West), [[Old Toronto]]\n* [[East York Town Centre]] (Millwood Road and Overlea Boulevard), [[East York]]\n* [[Eglinton Square Shopping Centre]] (Eglinton Avenue East and Victoria Park Avenue), Scarborough\n* Jane-Finch Mall ([[Jane and Finch]])), North York\n* [[Lawrence Allen Centre]] (formerly Lawrence Square Shopping Centre; renamed in late 2019) (Allen Road and Lawrence Avenue West), North York\n* Malvern Town Centre (Neilson Road and Tapscott Road), Scarborough\n* North York Sheridan Mall (Jane Street and Wilson Avenue), North York\n* [[Parkway Mall]] (Victoria Park Avenue and Ellesmere Road), Scarborough\n* [[Woodbine Centre]] (Rexdale Boulevard and Highway 27), Etobicoke\n* [[Woodside Square]] (McCowan Road and Finch Avenue East), Scarborough\n\nEthnic malls\n* [[Splendid China Mall]] (Steeles Avenue east of Kennedy Road), Scarborough; converted from [[Canadian Tire]]\n<!--This section is for shopping malls-->\n\n==Malls located within major office buildings==\n[[File:College Park December 2009.jpg|thumb|[[College Park (Toronto)|College Park]] is one of several buildings in Toronto that is used as an office complex and a shopping centre.]]\nOne configuration of shopping mall in Toronto is the self-contained type located within a commercial office building, sometimes around a central atrium. This type typically does not provide a surrounding parking lot. These malls typically house from a dozen to several dozen stores. Most of these are connected to a station of the [[Toronto subway]] system. In the case of the Hudson's Bay Centre, the mall connects the department store to the Toronto subway system at [[Bloor\u2013Yonge station]]. These malls are located in the core ([[Old Toronto]]), unless marked otherwise:\n* The [[Atrium on Bay]] (Dundas Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Canada Square Complex|Canada Square]] ([[Yonge-Eglinton|Yonge Street and Eglinton Avenue West]])\n* Chinatown Centre ([[Chinatown, Toronto|Chinatown]]); ethnic mall\n* [[College Park (Toronto)|College Park]] (Yonge Street and College Street)\n* [[The Crossways, Toronto|The Crossways]] (Bloor Street West and Dundas Street West)\n* Cumberland Terrace (Bay Street and Bloor Street West)\n* Dragon City ([[Chinatown, Toronto|Chinatown]]) (Dundas Street West and Spadina Avenue); ethnic mall\n* Dynasty Centre (Sheppard Avenue East and Midland Avenue), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]; ethnic mall\n* [[Empress Walk]] (Empress Avenue and Yonge Street), [[North York]]\n* Holt Renfrew Centre (Bloor Street West and Bay Street)\n* [[Hudson's Bay Centre]] (Bloor Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Manulife Centre]] (Bloor Street West and Bay Street)\n* [[Queens Quay (Toronto)|Queen's Quay]] Terminal (Queen's Quay West and York Street)\n* Sheppard Centre  (Sheppard Avenue East and Yonge Street), [[North York]]\n* Yonge Eglinton Centre ([[Yonge-Eglinton|Yonge Street and Eglinton Avenue West]])\n* [[Yorkville Village]] (formerly Hazelton Lanes) (Avenue Road and Yorkville Avenue)\n* [[York Mills Centre]] (York Mills Road and Yonge Street), North York\n\n===PATH underground shopping complex===\n[[File:Toronto PATH (15126928816).jpg|thumb|Signage for the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] from [[Scotia Plaza]]. The PATH connects most of [[Downtown Toronto|downtown]] and is the world's largest [[Underground city|underground shopping complex]].]]\nIn [[Downtown Toronto]], primarily in the [[Financial District, Toronto|Financial District]], there are interconnected shopping malls located one flight of stairs underground. The complex as a whole is named '[[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]]'. The Toronto Eaton Centre (see above) is connected to the complex. The complex has 1,200 stores, and according to ''[[Guinness World Records]]'', the PATH is the largest [[Underground city|underground shopping complex]] in the world with {{Convert|371600|m2|sqft|abbr=on}} of retail space.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toronto.ca/explore-enjoy/visitor-services/path-torontos-downtown-pedestrian-walkway/|title=PATH \u2013 Toronto's Downtown Pedestrian Walkway|date=15 August 2017|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>\n\n* [[Brookfield Place (Toronto)|Brookfield Place]] (bounded by Front Street West, Bay Street, Wellington Street West, and Yonge Street)\n* [[Commerce Court]] (Yonge Street and King Street West)\n* [[First Canadian Place]] (Bay Street and King Street West)\n* [[Metro Hall]] (John Street and King Street West)\n* [[Royal Bank Plaza]] (Bay Street and Front Street West)\n* [[Scotia Plaza]] (King Street West and Yonge Street)\n* [[Toronto-Dominion Centre]] (bounded by King Street West, Bay Street, Wellington Street West, and York Street)\n* [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] (Bay Street and Front Street West)\n\n==Open-air shopping plazas==\nOpen-air shopping plazas are larger collections of stores built with surrounding parking areas, with parking spaces separated from the storefronts by sidewalks. These shopping centres generally serve the local surrounding area and have a large proportion of family-run businesses, some of which are ethnic.\n[[File:Shops at Don Mills (37496324736).jpg|thumb|[[Shops at Don Mills]] is one of several open-air malls in Toronto.]]\n* Chartwell Plaza (Brimley Road and Huntingwood Drive), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Dragon Centre (Sheppard Avenue East and Glen Watford Drive), Scarborough; ethnic mall\n* Dufferin & Steeles Plaza [[North York]]\n* Dufferin Business Centre (Dufferin Street between Castlefield Avenue and the former [[York, Toronto|York]]-[[North York]] boundary), [[York, Toronto|York]]\n* Iranian Plaza (Yonge Street between Cummer Avenue and Steeles Avenue), North York; ethnic mall\n* Lawrence Plaza (Bathurst Street and Lawrence Avenue West), North York\n* Peanut Plaza (Don Mills Road and Van Horne Avenue), North York\n* Sheppard Plaza (Sheppard Avenue West and Bathurst Street), North York\n* [[Shops at Don Mills]] (Don Mills Road and Lawrence Avenue East), North York\n* Sunnybrook Plaza (Eglinton Avenue East and Bayview Avenue), [[East York]]\n* Tam O'Shanter Plaza (Sheppard Avenue East east of Kennedy Road), Scarborough\n* The Landmark (Steeles Avenue and Middlefield Road), Scarborough; ethnic mall\n* Victoria Terrace (Victoria Park Avenue and Lawrence Avenue East), North York\n* Whiteshield Plaza (Kennedy Road and Lawrence Avenue East), Scarborough\n* York Mills Gardens (Leslie Street and York Mills Road), North York\n\n==Power centres==\n[[Retail park|Power centres]] mainly consist of major national and international [[big-box store]]s with large amounts of parking space separate from the stores themselves, and which serve a larger area than the open-air shopping plazas do.\n[[File:Shoppers World Danforth.JPG|thumb|[[Shoppers World Danforth]] is an example of an early [[retail park|power centre]], one of several that can be found in the city.]]\n* Black Creek Super Value Centre (Rogers Road and Keele Street), [[York, Toronto|York]]\n* Crossroads (Weston Road and Highway 401), [[North York]]\n* Downsview Power Centre (unofficial name) (Dufferin Street and Wilson Avenue), North York\n* Dufferin and Steeles Power Centre (unofficial name) (Dufferin Street and Steeles Avenue), North York\n* [[Golden Mile, Toronto|Golden Mile]] (Eglinton Avenue East between Victoria Park Avenue and Birchmount Road), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n* Kennedy Commons (Kennedy Road and Highway 401), Scarborough\n* Leaside Centre (Eglinton Avenue East and Laird Drive), [[East York]]\n* [[Shoppers World Danforth]] (Danforth Avenue west of Victoria Park Avenue), East York\n* Queenswalk Centre (North Queen Street and Queensway), [[Etobicoke]]\n* Queensway Complex (Islington Avenue and Queensway), Etobicoke\n* [[Stock Yards Village]] (Keele Street/Weston Road and St. Clair Avenue West), [[Old Toronto]]\n\n==Flea markets==\nThe markets are housed indoors with stalls of independent vendors.\n* Downsview Park Merchant's Market, [[Downsview Park]] (Keele Street and Sheppard Avenue West), [[North York]]\n* Dr. Flea's, Highway 27 and Albion Road, [[Etobicoke]]\n* Jane Finch Flea Market, 1911 Finch Avenue West (Jane Street and Finch Avenue West), [[North York]]\n* Merchant's Flea Market, 1921 Eglinton Avenue East, (Warden Avenue and Eglinton Avenue East), [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]\n\n==Former shopping malls==\nThe following shopping malls have been demolished or closed. Some have been replaced by new strip plazas or re-developed for non-retail uses:\n<!--Please limit the list to those within Toronto's city limits-->\n[[File:Yonge-arcade-interior-1885.jpg|thumb|The original [[Arcade Building (Toronto)|Yonge Street Arcade]] building, c. 1885. The shopping centre was opened in 1884 and operated until it was demolished in 1954.]]\n* The original [[Arcade Building (Toronto)#Original Arcade building|Yonge Street Arcade]] (1884\u20131954) at 137 Yonge Street and consisting of 52 stores was considered Canada's first indoor mall. It was demolished in 1954 following two fires and was replaced in 1960 by the [[Arcade Building (Toronto)|Arcade Building]], which had a similar [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] style concourse on its main floor until 2008 when the floor was redeveloped with the arcade being replaced with a fitness centre and offices.\n* [[Galleria Shopping Centre (Toronto)|Galleria Shopping Centre]] (Dufferin Street and Dupont Street), Old Toronto; set to close for redevelopment in early 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reimaginegalleria.com/project/|title=Project|website=Reimagine Galleria}}</ref>\n* [[Golden Mile, Toronto#Golden Mile Plaza|Golden Mile Plaza]] (1954\u20131986) at Eglinton Avenue East and Victoria Park Avenue, demolished after 1986 fire and later replaced with a power centre named Golden Mile Mall.\n* Morningside Mall (1979\u20132002) at Morningside Avenue and Kingston Road, [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]; the indoor mall<ref>http://www.felixkalmenson.com/files/gimgs/42_historicize-pdf.jpg{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=Johnny Au |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> was demolished to make way for an outdoor big box plaza called Morningside Crossing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westhillnews.blogspot.ca/2007/11/morningside-crossing.html|title=Morningside Crossing|website=westhillnews.blogspot.ca}}</ref>\n* Rexdale Plaza (1957\u20132004), Islington Avenue and Rexdale Boulevard, [[Etobicoke]]<ref>[http://www.uer.ca/locations/show.asp?locid=20545 Urban Exploration Resource]</ref> and enclosed in 1972. Most stores closed by 2003 and demolition of south end in 2004 with north end of mall retained (with an [[Asian supermarket]] and a few small stores). Since 2004, its south end was redeveloped as an outdoor mall with [[Walmart Canada|Wal-Mart]] Supercentre as a stand-alone big box store.\n* Warden Woods Mall or Warden Power Centre (1970\u20132005) at Warden Avenue north of St. Clair Avenue East near [[Warden station]], [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]]<ref>[http://www.uer.ca/locations/show.asp?locid=23270 Urban Exploration Resource]</ref> was a full mall with three anchor stores (The Bay, Simpson's and a [[Knob Hill Farms]] grocery store) and later as clearance centre. It has since been demolished and replaced with townhouses.\n* Weston-Finch Mall (1960s\u20132006), Weston Road and Finch Avenue West, North York \u2014 former strip mall (with [[Zellers]], [[Canadian Tire]] and [[McDonald's Canada|McDonald's]] as tenants) and later as outlet facility; demolished 2006 and vacant lot{{when|date=August 2012}} awaiting redevelopment for rental apartments.\n*  Westside Mall, Eglinton Avenue West west of Caledonia Road, [[York, Toronto|York]] \u2014 replaced with a power centre of the same name during the early 2000s (with Canadian Tire, [[Rogers Plus]], [[FreshCo]] (renamed from Price Chopper), [[Dollar Tree Canada|Dollar Tree]] (formerly occupied by Shoppers Drug Mart) and [[Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce|CIBC]] as major tenants) and will be connected to [[Caledonia station]] of both GO Transit's Barrie line and the Toronto subway system in 2022.\n* [[Honeydale Mall]] (1973\u20132013): Located in [[Eatonville, Toronto|Eatonville]] neighbourhood of Toronto; officially closed on 28 June 2013.\n<!--Please limit the list to those within Toronto's city limits-->\n\n===Former flea markets===\n* Flea market at the southwest corner of Midland Avenue and Sheppard Avenue East is closed since the early 2000s and the property will be redeveloped concurrent with the [[Sheppard East LRT]]'s construction.\n* Dufferin and Steeles Flea Market, replaced with [[The Home Depot]].\n* Toronto Weston Flea Market, Old Weston Road and St. Clair Avenue West, [[Old Toronto]] (later relocated to a smaller site nearby on St. Clair Avenue West between Old Weston Road and GO Transit's Barrie Line)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[List of largest enclosed shopping malls in Canada]]\n* [[List of shopping malls in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Shopping Malls in the Golden Horseshoe}}\n{{Toronto}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Toronto| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of shopping malls|Toronto]]\n[[Category:Toronto-related lists|Shopping malls]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Ontario|shopping malls]]\n", "name_user": "PKT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFormer shopping malls:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_shopping_malls_in_Toronto"}
{"title_page": "Isaiah Stillman", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Isaiah Stillman\n|birth_date= 1793\n|death_date= 15 April {{death year and age|1861|1793}}\n|birth_place= [[Massachusetts]] \n|death_place= [[Kingston Mines, Illinois|Kingston]], [[Peoria County]], [[Illinois]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Major Isaiah Stillman.jpg\n|caption= Major Isaiah Stillman, Illinois militia leader\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= Illinois Militia\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[File:Union army maj rank insignia.jpg|35px]] [[Major (rank)|Major]]\n|commands=\n|unit=\n|battles= [[Black Hawk War]]\n*[[Battle of Stillman's Run]]\n|awards= \n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Isaiah Stillman''' (1793&ndash;15 April 1861)  was an [[Americans|American]] Cavalry [[Major]]  who led the [[Illinois]] [[militia]] in the first armed confrontation of the [[Black Hawk War]] against [[Black Hawk (chief)|Black Hawk]]'s [[Sauk people|Sauk]] Indian Band. The first armed confrontation would be named Battle of Old Man's Creek, but would later be named [[Battle of Stillman's Run|Stillman's Run]] after him.\n\nIsaiah Stillman was born and raised in the state of [[Massachusetts]], but he left the east and traveled to [[Illinois]] to become a trader of pots, pans, and other items.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\">[http://www.comportone.com/cpo/genealogy/articles/localhistory/BlackHawkWar.htm The Black Hawk War and Stillman's Run ] Retrieved on October 22, 2007</ref> For a time, he lived in [[Coopers Creek Landing]] in [[Fulton County, Illinois|Fulton County]], before deciding to join the Illinois [[militia]] as a [[Captain (land)|captain]] at the age of 35 in 1827.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> By the early part of 1832, Isaiah had attained the rank of [[Brigadier General-elect]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> With this new position, he gained the responsibility of defending everything west of the [[Illinois River]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> This land was mostly an empty place, with few First Nation's tribes and settlements.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> In April 1832, [[Governor of Illinois]] [[John Reynolds (Illinois politician)|John Reynolds]] ordered  Stillman to raise a battalion for the [[Illinois militia]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> He was unable to recruit a full battalion, so he was made a major rather than a general. The next year after Black Hawk War, he was promoted to general.\n\nHe died in [[Kingston Mines, Illinois]] on April 15, 1861, at the age of 67. He is buried in [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.historynet.com/wars_conflicts/american_indian_wars/3037561.html?featured=y&c=y Historynet\u2019s Black Hawk War]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070221024749/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/gal/stevens97.html#about Abraham Lincoln Historical Digitization Project]\n*[http://www.comportone.com/cpo/genealogy/articles/localhistory/BlackHawkWar.htm Black Hawk War]\n\n{{Black Hawk War (1832)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stillman, Isaiah}}\n[[Category:1793 births]]\n[[Category:1861 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of the Black Hawk War]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Burials in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{US-army-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Isaiah Stillman\n|birth_date= 1793\n|death_date= 15 April {{death year and age|1861|1793}}\n|birth_place= [[Massachusetts]] \n|death_place= [[Kingston Mines, Illinois|Kingston]], [[Peoria County]], [[Illinois]]\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|image= Major Isaiah Stillman.jpg\n|caption= Major Isaiah Stillman, Illinois militia leader\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch= Illinois Militia\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[File:Union army maj rank insignia.jpg|35px]] [[Major (rank)|Major]]\n|commands=\n|unit=\n|battles= [[Black Hawk War]]\n*[[Battle of Stillman's Run]]\n|awards= \n|laterwork=\n}}\n'''Isaiah Stillman''' (1793&ndash;15 April 1861)  was an [[Americans|American]] Cavalry [[Major]]  who led the [[Illinois]] [[militia]] in the first armed confrontation of the [[Black Hawk War]] against [[Black Hawk (chief)|Black Hawk]]'s [[Sauk people|Sauk]] Indian Band. The first armed confrontation would be named Battle of Old Man's Creek, but would later be named [[Battle of Stillman's Run|Stillman's Run]] after him.\n\nIsaiah Stillman was born and raised in the state of [[Massachusetts]], but he left the east and traveled to [[Illinois]] to become a trader of pots, pans, and other items.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\">[http://www.comportone.com/cpo/genealogy/articles/localhistory/BlackHawkWar.htm The Black Hawk War and Stillman's Run ] Retrieved on October 22, 2007</ref> For a time, he lived in [[Coopers Creek Landing]] in [[Fulton County, Illinois|Fulton County]], before deciding to join the Illinois [[militia]] as a [[Captain (land)|captain]] at the age of 35 in 1827.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> By the early part of 1832, Isaiah had attained the rank of [[Brigadier General-elect]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> With this new position, he gained the responsibility of defending everything west of the [[Illinois River]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> This land was mostly an empty place, with few First Nation's tribes and settlements.<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> In April 1832, [[Governor of Illinois]] [[John Reynolds (U.S. politician)|John Reynolds]] ordered  Stillman to raise a battalion for the [[Illinois militia]].<ref name=\"BHW&SR\" /> He was unable to recruit a full battalion, so he was made a major rather than a general. The next year after Black Hawk War, he was promoted to general.\n\nHe died in [[Kingston Mines, Illinois]] on April 15, 1861, at the age of 67. He is buried in [[Peoria, Illinois|Peoria]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.historynet.com/wars_conflicts/american_indian_wars/3037561.html?featured=y&c=y Historynet\u2019s Black Hawk War]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070221024749/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/gal/stevens97.html#about Abraham Lincoln Historical Digitization Project]\n*[http://www.comportone.com/cpo/genealogy/articles/localhistory/BlackHawkWar.htm Black Hawk War]\n\n{{Black Hawk War (1832)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stillman, Isaiah}}\n[[Category:1793 births]]\n[[Category:1861 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of the Black Hawk War]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Burials in Illinois]]\n\n\n{{US-army-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Reynolds(link changed toJohn Reynolds (Illinois politician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaiah_Stillman"}
{"title_page": "Shreve, Lamb & Harmon", "text_new": "[[Image:EmpireStateBuilding 2007 amk bw.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Empire State Building]]\n\n'''Shreve, Lamb, and Harmon''', founded as '''Shreve & Lamb''', was an [[architect|architectural firm]], best known for designing the [[Empire State Building]], the tallest building in the world at the time of its completion in 1931.\n\n==History== yes\nThe firm was founded in 1920 as Shreve & Lamb, a partnership of [[Richmond Shreve|Richmond Harold (\"R.H.\") Shreve]], a Canadian from [[Nova Scotia]], and [[William F. Lamb]], from [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\u2014Shreve was the administrator, while Lamb was the designer. The two met while working at [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]], and Shreve & Lamb was initially a Carr\u00e8re & Hastings firm. In 1924 the pair decided to leave Carr\u00e8re & Hastings and became an autonomous architectural company.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nIn 1929 [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]], from [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S., joined Shreve & Lamb, and the firm became Shreve, Lamb & Harmon.<ref name=\"Klose\">Klose, Oliivia. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110309215524/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2427.pdf \"500 Fifth Avenue Designation Report\"] [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] (December 14, 2010)</ref> Prior to joining the firm, Harmon's works included battle monuments at Tours, Cantigny and Somme-Py in France, a YMCA in [[Jerusalem]], and the Shelton Hotel in New York, U.S.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nFor the construction of the Empire State Building, the firm's most notable work, Lamb was responsible for the design, while Shreve's planning skills facilitated the completion of the construction in a year. Shreve's planning skills were recognized in New York and he was involved in projects beyond the firm, such as the [[Slum clearance]] Committee of New York.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nShreve, Lamb & Harmon primary focus was commercial office buildings and their work in this area was described as \"spare and functional\" in 2010 by the Landmarks Preservation Commission. However, the firm completed numerous residential projects, such as No. 130 East 57th Street, and this facet of the company's work was mainly conducted in neo-Tudor, as well as other popular historical styles of the 1920s.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nIt's not entirely clear when the company went out of business, with 1989 being a likely date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/archival/collections/ldpd_6622465/|title=Shreve Lamb & Harmon architectural records, 1930-1989\u00a0bulk 1937-1965|website=www.columbia.edu|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Notable buildings==\nAll buildings are located in [[New York City]] unless otherwise indicated:\n\n*[[Reynolds Building]], [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], 1929\n*[[521 Fifth Avenue]] (also known as the ''Lefcourt National Building''), 1929\n*[[740 Park Avenue]] (with [[Rosario Candela]]), 1930 \n*[[500 Fifth Avenue]], 1931, <!-- [[based in New York]] (heading says that) -->\n*[[Empire State Building]], 1930\u20131931 <!-- [[another one based in new york]] (heading says that)-->\n*[[14 Wall Street]] (formerly the ''Bankers Trust Company Building'') addition, 1931\u20131932\n*[[Joel W. Solomon Federal Building and United States Courthouse]] (with [[R. H. Hunt]]), [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]], 1932\n*[[99 John Deco Lofts]] (formerly ''The Great American Insurance Company Building''), 1933\n*[[Jerusalem International YMCA]] (architect [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]]), [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]], 1933\n*[[Acacia Building]], [[Washington, D.C.]], 1936\n*[[Hill Building]] (formerly the ''SunTrust Tower'', ''CCB Building'' or ''Central Carolina Bank'', and ''Durham Bank and Trust Building''), [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], North Carolina, 1935\u20131937\n*[[100 Ardsley Avenue West]] (Hudson House), Irvington, NY 1936\n*[[Lever Brothers Co. Headquarters (now MIT Sloan School, Building E52)]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], 1938\n*[[Hunter College]], 1940\n*[[Parkchester, Bronx|Parkchester]] buildings, 1939\u20131942\n*[[Best & Co.#Flagship store|Best & Company Building]] (demolished), 1947\n*[[Mutual of New York Building|1740 Broadway]] (formerly the ''MONY Building'' or ''Mutual of New York Building''), 1950\n*[[New York Supreme Court|New York Supreme Court, Kings County]], 1957\n*[[Columbia University|Carman Hall]], 1960\n*[[United Engineering Center]] (demolished in 1997), 1961\n*[[280 Park Avenue]] (formerly the ''Bankers Trust Building'', with [[Emery Roth & Sons]]), 1961\n*[[222 Broadway]] (formerly the ''Western Electric Building''), 1961\n*[[Calyon Building]] (formerly the ''Cr\u00e9dit Lyonnais Building'' and ''J. C. Penney Building''), 1964\n*[[Uniroyal Giant Tire]], [[Allen Park, Michigan|Allen Park]], [[Michigan]], 1964\n*[[245 Park Avenue]] (formerly the ''Bear Stearns Building'', ''American Brands Building'', and ''American Tobacco Company Building''), 1967\n*[[1250 Broadway]] (formerly the ''Cooper-Bregstein Building''), 1967\u20131968\n*[[475 Park Avenue South]], 1969\n*[[Gouverneur Hospital]], 1970\n*[[Textron Tower]] (formerly the ''40 Westminster Building'' and ''Old Stone Tower''), [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], 1972\n*[[55 Church Street]], [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], 1974\n*[[Deutsche Bank Building]] (formerly the Bankers Trust Plaza, now demolished), 1974\n*[[3 Park Avenue]], 1975\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n{{refimprove|date=June 2014}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shreve, Lamb and Harmon}}\n[[Category:Defunct architecture firms based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper architects]]\n[[Category:Design companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:EmpireStateBuilding 2007 amk bw.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Empire State Building]]\n\n'''Shreve, Lamb, and Harmon''', founded as '''Shreve & Lamb''', was an [[architect|architectural firm]], best known for designing the [[Empire State Building]], the tallest building in the world at the time of its completion in 1931.\n\n==History==\nThe firm was founded in 1920 as Shreve & Lamb, a partnership of [[Richmond Shreve|Richmond Harold (\"R.H.\") Shreve]], a Canadian from [[Nova Scotia]], and [[William F. Lamb]], from [[Brooklyn]], New York, U.S.\u2014Shreve was the administrator, while Lamb was the designer. The two met while working at [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]], and Shreve & Lamb was initially a Carr\u00e8re & Hastings firm. In 1924 the pair decided to leave Carr\u00e8re & Hastings and became an autonomous architectural company.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nIn 1929 [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]], from [[Chicago]], Illinois, U.S., joined Shreve & Lamb, and the firm became Shreve, Lamb & Harmon.<ref name=\"Klose\">Klose, Oliivia. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110309215524/http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/2427.pdf \"500 Fifth Avenue Designation Report\"] [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] (December 14, 2010)</ref> Prior to joining the firm, Harmon's works included battle monuments at Tours, Cantigny and Somme-Py in France, a YMCA in [[Jerusalem]], and the Shelton Hotel in New York, U.S.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nFor the construction of the Empire State Building, the firm's most notable work, Lamb was responsible for the design, while Shreve's planning skills facilitated the completion of the construction in a year. Shreve's planning skills were recognized in New York and he was involved in projects beyond the firm, such as the [[Slum clearance]] Committee of New York.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nShreve, Lamb & Harmon primary focus was commercial office buildings and their work in this area was described as \"spare and functional\" in 2010 by the Landmarks Preservation Commission. However, the firm completed numerous residential projects, such as No. 130 East 57th Street, and this facet of the company's work was mainly conducted in neo-Tudor, as well as other popular historical styles of the 1920s.<ref name=\"Klose\" />\n\nIt's not entirely clear when the company went out of business, with 1989 being a likely date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/archival/collections/ldpd_6622465/|title=Shreve Lamb & Harmon architectural records, 1930-1989\u00a0bulk 1937-1965|website=www.columbia.edu|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Notable buildings==\nAll buildings are located in [[New York City]] unless otherwise indicated:\n\n*[[Reynolds Building]], [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], 1929\n*[[521 Fifth Avenue]] (also known as the ''Lefcourt National Building''), 1929\n*[[740 Park Avenue]] (with [[Rosario Candela]]), 1930 \n*[[500 Fifth Avenue]], 1931, <!-- [[based in New York]] (heading says that) -->\n*[[Empire State Building]], 1930\u20131931 <!-- [[another one based in new york]] (heading says that)-->\n*[[14 Wall Street]] (formerly the ''Bankers Trust Company Building'') addition, 1931\u20131932\n*[[Joel W. Solomon Federal Building and United States Courthouse]] (with [[R. H. Hunt]]), [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], [[Tennessee]], 1932\n*[[99 John Deco Lofts]] (formerly ''The Great American Insurance Company Building''), 1933\n*[[Jerusalem International YMCA]] (architect [[Arthur Loomis Harmon]]), [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]], 1933\n*[[Acacia Building]], [[Washington, D.C.]], 1936\n*[[Hill Building]] (formerly the ''SunTrust Tower'', ''CCB Building'' or ''Central Carolina Bank'', and ''Durham Bank and Trust Building''), [[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]], North Carolina, 1935\u20131937\n*[[100 Ardsley Avenue West]] (Hudson House), Irvington, NY 1936\n*[[Lever Brothers Co. Headquarters (now MIT Sloan School, Building E52)]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], 1938\n*[[Hunter College]], 1940\n*[[Parkchester, Bronx|Parkchester]] buildings, 1939\u20131942\n*[[Best & Co.#Flagship store|Best & Company Building]] (demolished), 1947\n*[[Mutual of New York Building|1740 Broadway]] (formerly the ''MONY Building'' or ''Mutual of New York Building''), 1950\n*[[New York Supreme Court|New York Supreme Court, Kings County]], 1957\n*[[Columbia University|Carman Hall]], 1960\n*[[United Engineering Center]] (demolished in 1997), 1961\n*[[280 Park Avenue]] (formerly the ''Bankers Trust Building'', with [[Emery Roth & Sons]]), 1961\n*[[222 Broadway]] (formerly the ''Western Electric Building''), 1961\n*[[Calyon Building]] (formerly the ''Cr\u00e9dit Lyonnais Building'' and ''J. C. Penney Building''), 1964\n*[[Uniroyal Giant Tire]], [[Allen Park, Michigan|Allen Park]], [[Michigan]], 1964\n*[[245 Park Avenue]] (formerly the ''Bear Stearns Building'', ''American Brands Building'', and ''American Tobacco Company Building''), 1967\n*[[1250 Broadway]] (formerly the ''Cooper-Bregstein Building''), 1967\u20131968\n*[[475 Park Avenue South]], 1969\n*[[Gouverneur Hospital]], 1970\n*[[Textron Tower]] (formerly the ''40 Westminster Building'' and ''Old Stone Tower''), [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]], 1972\n*[[55 Church Street]], [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], 1974\n*[[Deutsche Bank Building]] (formerly the Bankers Trust Plaza, now demolished), 1974\n*[[3 Park Avenue]], 1975\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n{{refimprove|date=June 2014}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shreve, Lamb and Harmon}}\n[[Category:Defunct architecture firms based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper architects]]\n[[Category:Design companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "86.86.32.160", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shreve,_Lamb_%26_Harmon"}
{"title_page": "Illinois's 1st congressional district", "text_new": "{{short description|Congressional district}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox U.S. congressional district\n|state = Illinois\n|district number = 1\n|image name = Illinois US Congressional District 1 (since 2013).tif\n|image width = 400\n|image caption = Illinois's 1st congressional district since January 3, 2013\n|representative = [[Bobby Rush]]\n|party = Democratic\n|residence = Chicago\n|english area =258\n|metric area = 669\n|percent urban = 99.0\n|percent rural = 1.0\n|population = 706,550\n|population year =2018 est.\n|median income = $55,959<ref>https://www.census.gov/mycd/?st=17&cd=01</ref>\n|percent black = 50.1 <ref>https://www.census.gov/mycd/?st=17&cd=01</ref>\n|percent white = 43.0 <ref>https://www.census.gov/mycd/?st=17&cd=01</ref>\n|percent asian = 2.5\n|percent native american = 0.2\n|percent native hawaiian = 0.0\n|percent hispanic = 10.7\n|percent other race = 2.7\n|percent more than one race =1.7\n|percent blue collar = \n|percent white collar = \n|percent gray collar = \n|cpvi = D+28<ref name=Cook>{{cite web|url=http://cookpolitical.com/file/Arranged_by_State_District.pdf|title=Partisan Voting Index \u2013 Districts of the 115th Congress|publisher=The Cook Political Report|date=April 7, 2017|accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Barone2014>\n  {{cite book\n    |last=Barone |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Barone (pundit)\n    |authorlink2=Chuck McCutcheon |first2=Chuck |last2=McCutcheon\n    |title=The Almanac of American Politics 2014 |year=2013\n    |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |location=[[Chicago]]\n    |isbn=978-0-226-10544-4 |page=552}} Copyright [[National Journal]].</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Illinois's first congressional district''' is a [[congressional district]] in the U.S. state of [[Illinois]]. Based in [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook County]], the district includes much of the South Side of Chicago, and continues southwest to [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]].\n\nFrom 2003 to early 2013 it extended into the city's [[Chicago metropolitan area|southwest suburbs]] until reaching the border of [[Will County, Illinois|Will County]], and covered {{convert|97.84|sqmi|km2}}, making it one of the [[List of United States congressional districts by area|40 smallest districts]] in the U.S. (although there are four smaller districts in Illinois). The district had a population that was 65% African American, the highest percentage of any congressional district in the nation. {{citation needed|date=February 2014}} It includes the home of former [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]].\n\nThe 1st is a [[majority-minority]] district, and has been since at least the 1920s. In 1929, it became the first district in the 20th century to send an [[African American]] to Congress. Since redistricting by the state legislature after the 2010 census, it is 51.3% African American, 40.6% white, and 9.8% Hispanic in population. The district is represented by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Bobby Rush]], who was re-elected in 2018, and has been elected continuously in the 1st district since 1992.\n\n==2011 redistricting==\nIn 2011, following the [[United States Census, 2010|2010 census]], the state legislature redistricted. It expanded the district to cover parts of [[Cook County, Illinois|Cook]] and [[Will County, Illinois|Will]] Counties.  After [[redistricting]], all or parts of [[Alsip, Illinois|Alsip]], [[Blue Island, Illinois|Blue Island]], [[Calumet Park, Illinois|Calumet Park]], [[Chicago]], [[Country Club Hills, Illinois|Country Club Hills]], [[Crestwood, Illinois|Crestwood]], [[Dixmoor, Illinois|Dixmoor]], [[Elwood, Illinois|Elwood]], [[Evergreen Park, Illinois|Evergreen Park]], [[Frankfort, Illinois|Frankfort]], [[Frankfort Square, Illinois|Frankfort Square]], [[Harvey, Illinois|Harvey]], [[Manhattan, Illinois|Manhattan]], [[Markham, Illinois|Markham]], [[Merrionette Park, Illinois|Merrionette Park]], [[Midlothian, Illinois|Midlothian]], [[Mokena, Illinois|Mokena]], [[New Lenox, Illinois|New Lenox]], [[Oak Forest, Illinois|Oak Forest]], [[Oak Lawn, Illinois|Oak Lawn]], [[Orland Hills, Illinois|Orland Hills]], [[Orland Park, Illinois|Orland Park]], [[Palos Heights, Illinois|Palos Heights]], [[Posen, Illinois|Posen]], [[Riverdale, Illinois|Riverdale]], [[Robbins, Illinois|Robbins]], [[Tinley Park, Illinois|Tinley Park]], and [[Worth, Illinois|Worth]] are included.<ref>[http://elections.il.gov/Downloads/VotingInformation/PDF/2011Districts/2011CongDist1.pdf Illinois Congressional District 1], Illinois Board of Elections</ref> The representative for these districts were elected in the 2012 primary and general elections, and the boundaries became effective on January 3, 2013.\n\n==Composition until 2013==\nThe district was adjacent to the [[Illinois's 2nd congressional district|2nd District]] to the east and south, the [[Illinois's 7th congressional district|7th District]] to the north, and the [[Illinois's 3rd congressional district|3rd]] and [[Illinois's 13th congressional district|13th Districts]] to the west, and also bordered the [[Illinois's 11th congressional district|11th District]] at its southwest corner. The district's northeast border followed [[Lake Michigan]]'s shoreline for almost a mile.\n\nThe district was created following the [[United States Census, 1830|1830 U.S. Census]] and came into existence in 1833, five months before Chicago was organized as a town; the state was previously represented in [[United States House of Representatives|the U.S. House of Representatives]] with representative elected on an [[Illinois's At-large congressional district|at-large]] basis. The district included [[Little Egypt (region)|Southwestern Illinois]] until 1853.<ref name=ParsonsI>{{cite book |last=Parsons |first=Stanley B. |author2=William W. Beach |author3=Dan Hermann |title=United States Congressional Districts 1788\u20131841 |year=1978 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, CT |isbn=0-8371-9828-3 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/unitedstatescong0000pars_q4s3/page/302 302\u2013304] |url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatescong0000pars_q4s3/page/302 }}</ref><ref name=ParsonsII>{{cite book |last=Parsons |first=Stanley B. |author2=William W. Beach |author3=Michael J. Dubin  |title=United States Congressional Districts and Data, 1843\u20131883 |year=1986 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, CT |isbn=0-313-22045-X |pages=7\u20138 }}</ref> It included the state's [[Northern Illinois|northern edge]] until 1863.<ref name=ParsonsIII>Parsons, et al. (1986), pp. 53\u201354.</ref> Since that time, the district has included all or part of Cook County; since 1883 the population of the district has been primarily residing on [[Chicago's South Side]]. Historical populations reflected waves of immigration into the area: previous majority populations were ethnic Irish, German, and east European. Beginning in the mid-19th century, the Irish were the first to establish their physical and political control of the area within the city's South Side.\n\nThe current 1st district has a [[minority-majority]] population: 51.3% of the residents are [[African American (U.S. Census)|African-American]].<ref name=Barone2014/> <!-- has the highest percentage (65.5) of [[African American (U.S. Census)|African-American]] residents among congressional districts in the nation.{{cn|date=February 2014}} --> It has been represented in Congress by African Americans since 1929. Tens of thousands of African Americans moved to Chicago from the rural South in the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]]. They were confined by discrimination to the South Side of Chicago and gradually replaced ethnic whites who moved out to suburbs. At one point during the 1980s, more than 90% of the district's residents were black. <ref name=CQ1980s>{{cite book |last=Gottron |first=Martha V. (ed.) |title=Congressional Districts in the 1980s |year=1983 |publisher=Congressional Quarterly |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=0-87187-264-1 |page=156 }}</ref> \n\nWhile successive redistrictings have given the district a larger percentage of white voters, it is still one of the most reliably Democratic districts in the country; with a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of D+28, it is the fourth most Democratic district of the eight that divide Chicago. The district has not sent a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the U.S. House of Representatives since [[United States House elections, 1934|1935]]. After the [[civil rights movement]] gained support from national Democratic Party for major legislation to restore constitutional rights, including the franchise in the South, most African Americans shifted to support the Democratic Party. Democratic congressional candidates routinely receive over 80% of the vote here. The Democratic trend runs right through to the national level; since the 1950s, Democratic presidential candidates have usually carry the district with well over 70 percent of the vote, and have done no worse than 64 percent/\n\n===Geography===\nBased in Chicago, the district includes the neighborhoods of [[Auburn Gresham, Chicago|Auburn Gresham]], [[Burnside, Chicago|Burnside]], [[Chatham, Chicago|Chatham]] and [[Greater Grand Crossing, Chicago|Greater Grand Crossing]]; almost all of [[West Englewood, Chicago|West Englewood]]; the portion of [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] south of 57th Street; the portion of [[Woodlawn, Chicago|Woodlawn]] west of [[Stony Island Avenue]] (i.e. excluding [[Jackson Park (Chicago)|Jackson Park]]); the southern half of [[Kenwood, Chicago|Kenwood]] (home of President [[Barack Obama]]); the eastern portion of [[Ashburn, Chicago|Ashburn]]; parts of [[Avalon Park, Chicago|Avalon Park]], [[Calumet Heights, Chicago|Calumet Heights]], [[Chicago Lawn, Chicago|Chicago Lawn]], [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]], [[Grand Boulevard, Chicago|Grand Boulevard]], [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]], [[Morgan Park, Chicago|Morgan Park]], [[New City, Chicago|New City]], [[Oakland, Chicago|Oakland]], [[Roseland, Chicago|Roseland]], [[South Shore, Chicago|South Shore]], [[Washington Heights, Chicago|Washington Heights]] and [[Washington Park, Chicago (neighborhood)|Washington Park]]; the portion of [[Beverly, Chicago|Beverly]] southeast of 97th Street and Prospect Avenue; the portion of [[West Pullman, Chicago|West Pullman]] southwest of 119th Street and Racine Avenue; and approximately two square blocks at the northwest corner of [[South Chicago, Chicago|South Chicago]].\n\nThe district's area south of [[95th Street (Chicago)|95th Street]] is almost entirely west of [[Interstate 57]]. The district includes the municipalities of [[Crestwood, Illinois|Crestwood]], [[Evergreen Park, Illinois|Evergreen Park]], [[Midlothian, Illinois|Midlothian]], [[Posen, Illinois|Posen]] and [[Robbins, Illinois|Robbins]], nearly all of [[Alsip, Illinois|Alsip]], [[Blue Island, Illinois|Blue Island]] and [[Oak Forest, Illinois|Oak Forest]], parts of [[Calumet Park, Illinois|Calumet Park]], [[Dixmoor, Illinois|Dixmoor]], [[Markham, Illinois|Markham]], [[Orland Hills, Illinois|Orland Hills]], [[Orland Park, Illinois|Orland Park]], [[Palos Heights, Illinois|Palos Heights]], [[Tinley Park, Illinois|Tinley Park]] and [[Worth, Illinois|Worth]], and some small sections of [[Country Club Hills, Illinois|Country Club Hills]] and [[Riverdale, Illinois|Riverdale]].\n\n===Demographics===\nIn the twentieth century after the Great Migration from the South and concentration of blacks on the South Side due to ''de facto'' residential segregation, the district became the nation's first with a black-majority population. Since the 1920s, it has included the central area of Chicago's South Side African-American community. Over 85% of the district's residents were black during the period from the 1950s through the 1980s, but redistricting since that time \u2013 which redrew the district lines with the goal of maintaining three Chicago districts with black populations exceeding 60% \u2013 has reduced the percentage of black residents in the district to 70% in the 1990s. The current figure is 65%. Outward migration has caused the South Side's population to decrease over the years, and the district was expanded geographically to the southwest to gain residents, particularly as the state's congressional delegation has been reduced in numbers due to population changes and reapportionment. The district, which covered only nine square miles in the 1950s, is now more than ten times that size. Nearly half its current area was added for the 2000s.\n\nThe district's population dropped by 27% in the 1950s,<ref>{{cite book |title=Congressional District Data Book: Districts of the 87th Congress |year=1961 |publisher=U.S. Bureau of the Census |location=Washington, D.C. |page=16 }}</ref> and by 20% in both the 1970s and 1980s, due to outward migration for suburbanization and because of people leaving the area due to loss of jobs.<ref name=CQ1980s/><ref>{{cite book |title=Congressional Districts in the 1990s: A Portrait of America |year=1993 |publisher=Congressional Quarterly |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=0-87187-722-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/congressionaldis0000unse_i0y7/page/235 235] |url=https://archive.org/details/congressionaldis0000unse_i0y7/page/235 }}</ref> In redistricting after the [[United States Census, 1990|1990 U.S. Census]], the district was extended into the suburbs for the first time in 90 years. Chicago is home to 70% of the district's residents (down from 90% in the 1990s),<ref>{{cite book |last=Tarr |first=David R. (ed.) |title=Congressional Districts in the 2000s: A Portrait of America |year=2003 |publisher=CQ Press |location=Washington, D.C. |isbn=1-56802-849-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/congressionaldis0000unse_b6v5/page/296 296] |url=https://archive.org/details/congressionaldis0000unse_b6v5/page/296 }}</ref> although roughly 60% of the district's area is outside the city border. The district's white population (almost 30% of its residents) is concentrated in the suburban areas and in a few Chicago neighborhoods such as Hyde Park.<ref>See [http://fastfacts.census.gov/servlet/CWSThematicMapFramesetServlet?_bm=y&-oldGeo=50000US1701&-_MapEvent=displayBy&-tm_name=DEC_2000_110H_M00265&-ds_name=DEC_2000_110H&-ActiveGeoDiv=&-back=/servlet/CWSFacts%3F_event%3DChangeGeoContext%26geo_id%3D50000US1701%26_geoContext%3D01000US%257C04000US17%257C50000US1711%26_street%3D%26_county%3D%26_cd%3D50000US1701%26_cityTown%3D%26_state%3D04000US17%26_zip%3D%26_lang%3Den%26_sse%3Don%26ActiveGeoDiv%3D%26_useEV%3D%26pctxt%3Dfph%26pgsl%3D500%26_content%3D%26_keyword%3D%26_industry%3D&-pgsl=500&-redoLog=false&-geo_id=50000US1701&-_dBy=511&-pctxt=fph U.S. Census Bureau map] showing distribution of district's white population.</ref> The district's largest white ethnic groups are [[Irish American|Irish]] (7.1%), [[German American|German]] (6.2%), [[Polish American|Polish]] (4.5%) and [[Italian American|Italian]] (3.2%),<ref>''Congressional Districts in the 2000s: A Portrait of America'', p. 298.</ref> mirroring the demographics of the neighboring third and thirteenth Congressional Districts. There are also sizable [[Dutch American|Dutch]], [[Swedish American|Swedish]], [[Czech American|Czech]], [[Palestinian American|Palestinian]], [[Greek American|Greek]] and [[Lithuanian American|Lithuanian]] populations in the area of Oak Forest, Orland Park and Tinley Park, the district's three largest suburbs.\n\nThe Kenwood-Hyde Park area for several decades had a significant [[American Jews|Jewish]] community. Existing buildings attest to its history, as the former Kehilath Anshe Ma'ariv temple (its second location) has been the headquarters of [[Jesse Jackson]]'s [[Rainbow/PUSH|Operation PUSH/Rainbow Coalition]] since 1971 [http://ecuip.lib.uchicago.edu/diglib/social/cityofneighborhoods/southlakefront/con_tour_f-g.html]. The area also includes a notable presence of [[African American Muslims|Black Muslims]] and is the home of [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]] in Kenwood.\n\nAs of 2000, 38% of the district's adult residents were married. {{Needs expansion for other demographic data if this is to be included}}\n\n==Presidential election results==\n:''This table indicates how the district has voted in [[United States presidential election|U.S. presidential elections]]; election results reflect voting in the district as it was configured at the time of the election, not as it is configured today. The candidate who received the most votes in the district is listed first; the candidate who won the election nationally is in CAPS, and the candidate who won the state of Illinois is indicated with a \u2020.''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Election\n! District winner\n! Runner up\n! Other candidates\n\n|-\n| [[1852 United States presidential election|1852]]<ref name=Moses>Vote totals from 1852 to 1868 are based on cumulative county totals as listed in ''Illinois: Historical and Statistical'' (1892), [[John Moses (Illinois)|John Moses]], Chicago: Fergus Printing Co., pp. 1208\u20131209.</ref>\n| {{Party shading/Whig}}|[[Winfield Scott|Scott]] (W), 6,992 (42%)\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Franklin Pierce|PIERCE]]\u2020 (D), 6,948 (41%)\n| [[John P. Hale|Hale]] ([[Free Soil Party|Free Soil]]), 2,885 (17%)\n\n|-\n| [[1856 United States presidential election|1856]]<ref name=Moses/>\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[John C. Fr\u00e9mont|Fr\u00e9mont]] (R), 18,247 (73%)\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[James Buchanan|BUCHANAN]]\u2020 (D), 5,991 (24%)\n| [[Millard Fillmore|Fillmore]] ([[Know Nothing|American]]), 677 (3%)\n\n|-\n| [[1860 United States presidential election|1860]]<ref name=Moses/>\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Abraham Lincoln|LINCOLN]]\u2020 (R), 21,436 (70%)\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Stephen A. Douglas|Douglas]] (D), 8,940 (29%)\n| [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|Bell]] ([[Constitutional Union Party (United States)|Constitutional Union]]), 99 (0.3%); [[John C. Breckinridge|Breckinridge]] (D), 62 (0.2%)\n\n|-\n| [[1864 United States presidential election|1864]]<ref name=Moses/>\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Abraham Lincoln|LINCOLN]]\u2020 (R), 18,667 (81%)\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[George B. McClellan|McClellan]] (D), 4,351 (19%)\n|\n|-\n| [[1868 United States presidential election|1868]]<ref name=Moses/>\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Ulysses S. Grant|GRANT]]\u2020 (R), 27,527 (59%)\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Horatio Seymour|Seymour]] (D), 19,104 (41%)\n|\n|-\n| 1872<br/>\u2026<br/>1948\n| colspan=3 | {{dm|date=February 2020}}\n\n|-\n| [[1952 United States presidential election|1952]]<ref name=DataBook1961>''Congressional District Data Book: Districts of the 87th Congress'', p. 17.</ref>\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Adlai Stevenson II|Stevenson]] (D), 99,224 (75%)\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower|EISENHOWER]]\u2020 (R), 33,805 (25%)\n|\n|-\n| [[1956 United States presidential election|1956]]<ref name=DataBook1961/>\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Adlai Stevenson II|Stevenson]] (D), 68,266 (64%)\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower|EISENHOWER]]\u2020 (R), 38,827 (36%)\n|\n|-\n| [[1960 United States presidential election|1960]]<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1960election.pdf</ref>\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[John F. Kennedy|KENNEDY]]\u2020 (D), 75,938 (77.80%)\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] (R), 21,660 (22.19%)}\n\n|-\n| [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]]<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/1964election.pdf</ref>\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}}|[[Lyndon B. Johnson|JOHNSON]]\u2020 (D), 150,953 (84.91%)\n| {{Party shading/Republican}}|[[Barry Goldwater|Goldwater]] (R), 26,823 (15.08%)\n\n|-\n| [[1968 United States presidential election|1968]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Barone |fi