JBrice.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[John Blake Rice|John B. Rice]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nowrap | March 4, 1873 \u2013<br/>December 17, 1874\n| rowspan=2 | {{USCongressOrdinal|43}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Retired and then died.\n| rowspan=4 | '''1873 \u2013 1883'''<br/>{{Small|Restructured and now included [[DuPage County, Illinois|DuPage County]], the thirteen townships comprising the southern half of Cook County ([[Bloom Township, Cook County, Illinois|Bloom]], [[Bremen Township, Cook County, Illinois|Bremen]], [[Calumet Township, Cook County, Illinois|Calumet]], [[Hyde Park Township, Cook County, Illinois|Hyde Park]], Lake, [[Lemont Township, Cook County, Illinois|Lemont]], [[Lyons Township, Cook County, Illinois|Lyons]], [[Orland Township, Cook County, Illinois|Orland]], [[Palos Township, Cook County, Illinois|Palos]], [[Rich Township, Cook County, Illinois|Rich]], [[Riverside Township, Cook County, Illinois|Riverside]], [[Thornton Township, Cook County, Illinois|Thornton]], [[Worth Township, Cook County, Illinois|Worth]]), and the entire South Side and part of the West side of Chicago. The Chicago portion of the district began [[Chicago Loop|downtown]] and extended south to 39th Street (now Pershing Road) east of the [[Chicago River]] and south of the river and the [[Illinois and Michigan Canal]], with its western boundary being [[Western Avenue (Chicago)|Western Avenue]]; on the west side, the district included the area between 16th Street on the north and the river and canal on the south, with the city's western boundary then being Crawford Avenue (now [[Pulaski Road (Chicago)|Pulaski Road]]).<ref>Parsons, et al. (1986), pp. 159\u2013160.</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| colspan=2 | ''Vacant''\n| nowrap | December 17, 1874 \u2013<br/>February 1, 1875\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:BernardGCaulfield.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Bernard G. Caulfield]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| nowrap | February 1, 1875 \u2013<br/>March 3, 1877\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|43|44}}\n| [[1874 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Elected in 1874]].<br/>[[1875 Illinois's 1st congressional district special election|Also elected to finish Rice's term]].<br/>[[1874 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1874]].<br/>Retired.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:WilliamAldrich.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[William Aldrich]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nowrap | March 4, 1877 \u2013<br/>March 3, 1883\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|45|47}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Lost renomination.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | '''[[Ransom W. Dunham]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nowrap | March 4, 1883 \u2013<br/>March 3, 1889\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|48|50}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}\n| rowspan=3 | '''1883 \u2013 1895'''<br/>{{Small|Remained identical to its previous configuration, except that it no longer included DuPage County or the portion of Chicago west of [[Clark Street (Chicago)|Clark Street]] between 16th and 39th Streets.<ref>{{cite book | last=Parsons | first=Stanley B. | author2=Michael J. Dubin | author3=Karen Toombs Parsons | title=United States Congressional Districts, 1883\u20131913 | year=1990 | publisher=Greenwood Press | location=Westport, CT | isbn=0-313-26482-1 | pages=23\u201327 }}</ref> Illinois gained two additional representatives following the [[United States Census, 1890|1890 Census]], but they were elected on an at-large basis for the 1893\u20131895 term before redistricting occurred, and the previous decade's districting remained in effect.<ref>Parsons, et al. (1990), pp. 182\u2013186.</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Abner Taylor (Illinois Congressman).