llinois's districts were not redrawn until 1947, taking effect for the 1948 elections.<ref>{{cite book | last=Barrett | first=Edward A. (ed.) | title=Blue Book of the State of Illinois, 1947\u20131948 | publisher=State of Illinois | location=Springfield, IL | page=110 }}</ref> In [[1928 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|1928]], [[Oscar Stanton De Priest|Oscar De Priest]] became the first African American elected to Congress in the 20th century.}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Portrait of Martin B. Madden.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Martin B. Madden]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nowrap | March 4, 1905 \u2013<br/>April 27, 1928\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|59|70}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Died.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| colspan=2 | ''Vacant''\n| nowrap | April 27, 1928 \u2013<br/>March 3, 1929\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Oscar Stanton De Priest.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Oscar Stanton De Priest|Oscar S. De Priest]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| nowrap | March 4, 1929 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1935\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|71|73}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Lost re-election.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Arthur W. Mitchell.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Arthur W. Mitchell]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| nowrap | January 3, 1935 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1943\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|74|77}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Retired.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=4 align=left | [[File:William L Dawson.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[William L. Dawson (politician)|William L. Dawson]]'''\n| rowspan=4 {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| rowspan=4 nowrap | January 3, 1943 \u2013<br/>November 9, 1970\n| rowspan=4 | {{USCongressOrdinal|78|91}}\n| rowspan=4 | {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Died.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| '''1949 \u2013 1963'''<br/>{{Small|Included that part of Chicago bounded on the north by the river; on the east by the lake to Pershing Road and by Cottage Grove Avenue from Pershing to 71st Street and South Chicago Avenue; on the south by Marquette Road from State Street to South Chicago Avenue, following that southeast to 71st and Cottage Grove; and on the west by Wallace Street (from the river to 25th Street), Canal Street (25th to 31st Street), Wentworth (31st to 43rd Street), the railroad between State and Wentworth (43rd to 59th Street) and State Street (59th to Marquette).<ref>Barrett, pp. 113\u2013114.</ref> The same boundaries were maintained in the redistricting after 1950.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional District Atlas of the United States | year=1960 | publisher=[[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Bureau of the Census]] | location=Washington, D.C. | pages=18\u201320 }}</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| '''1963 \u2013 1967'''<br/>{{Small|Included that part of Chicago between 31st and 99th Streets bounded on the west by Wentworth (31st to Garfield Boulevard), the railroad 1/4-mile east of Halsted (Garfield to 59th), Halsted (59th to 63rd), State Street (63rd to 83rd) and Stewart Avenue (83rd to 99th), and bounded on the east by the lake (31st to 46th), Cottage Grove (46th to 65th) and [[Stony Island Avenue]] (65th to 99th).<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional District Data Book: Districts of the 88th Congress | year=1963 | publisher=U.S. Bureau of the Census | location=Washington, D.C. | pages=125\u2013127 }}</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=3 | '''1967 \u2013 1973'''<br/>{{Small|Additional redistricting for the 1967\u20131969 term. All of the district's previous territory was retained, but it was extended further north as far as [[Cermak Road]], with its western boundary being the railroad between State and Wentworth (Cermak to 28th Street) and then Wentworth (28th to Garfield). In addition, a small area east of Woodlawn Avenue between 46th and 47th Streets was added.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional District Data Book, Illinois supplement | year=1966 | publisher=U.S. Bureau of the Census | location=Washington, D.C. | pages=2\u20134 }}</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| colspan=2 | ''Vacant''\n| nowrap | November 9, 1970 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1971\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=2 align=left | [[File:RalphHMetcalfe1977.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Ralph Metcalfe]]'''\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| rowspan=2 nowrap | January 3, 1971 \u2013<br/>October 10, 1978\n| rowspan=2 | {{USCongressOrdinal|92|95}}\n| rowspan=2 | {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Died.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=4 | '''1973 \u2013 1983'''<br/>{{Small|Included that part of Chicago between 31st and 103rd Streets bounded on the west by King Drive (31st to 35th), State (35th to Pershing), the railroad 1/4-mile west of State (Pershing to Garfield), King Drive (Garfield to Marquette), Yale Avenue (Marquette to 69th), Harvard Avenue (69th to 70th), Stewart (70th to 71st), Halsted (71st to [[95th Street (Chicago)|95th]]), the railroad 1/2-mile east of Halsted (95th to 99th) and State (99th to 103rd), and on the east by the lake (31st to 71st Street/South Shore Drive), Yates Boulevard (71st to 73rd), Jeffery Boulevard (73rd to 75th) and Stony Island, continuing onto the [[Bishop Ford Freeway|Calumet Expressway]] (75th to 103rd, with minor variation at 95th).<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional District Data Book: 93rd Congress | year=1973 | publisher=U.S. Bureau of the Census | location=Washington, D.C. | pages=145, 147\u2013148 }}</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| colspan=2 | ''Vacant''\n| nowrap | October 10, 1978 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1979\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Bennett Stewart.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Bennett M. Stewart]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| nowrap | January 3, 1979 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1981\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|96}}\n| {{Data missing|date=February 2020}}<br/>Lost renomination.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=2 align=left | [[File:Washington h.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Harold Washington]]'''\n| rowspan=2 {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| rowspan=2 nowrap | January 3, 1981 \u2013<br/>April 30, 1983\n| rowspan=2 | {{USCongressOrdinal|97|98}}\n| rowspan=2 | [[1980 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Elected in 1980]].<br/>[[1982 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1982]].<br/>Resigned to become [[Mayor of Chicago]].\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=3 | '''1983 \u2013 1993'''<br/>{{Small|The only remaining district entirely within the city of Chicago, and included that area between Cermak Road and 103rd Street bounded on the west by Federal Street (Cermak to 25th), the railroad 1/4-mile west of State (25th to 35th), the railroad 1/2-mile east of Halsted (35th to 42nd and 43rd to 47th), Stewart (42nd to 43rd), Morgan Street (47th to 48th), Racine Avenue (48th to Garfield), Peoria Street (Garfield to 56th), Green Street (56th to 57th) and Halsted (57th to 103rd), and on the east by the lake (Cermak to 73rd) and Yates (73rd to 103rd).<ref>''Congressional Districts in the 1980s'', p. 163.</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| colspan=2 | ''Vacant''\n| nowrap | April 30, 1983 \u2013<br/>August 23, 1983\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| align=left | [[File:Rep. Charles Hayes.jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Charles Hayes (politician)|Charles A. Hayes]]'''\n| {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| nowrap | August 23, 1983 \u2013<br/>January 3, 1993\n| {{USCongressOrdinal|98|102}}\n| [[1983 Illinois's 1st congressional district special election|Elected to finish Washington's term]]<br/>[[1984 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1984]].<br/>[[1986 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1986]].<br/>[[1988 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1988]].<br/>[[1990 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1990]].<br/>Lost renomination.\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| rowspan=3 align=left | [[File:Bobby Rush official portrait (cropped).jpg|100px]]<br/>'''[[Bobby Rush]]'''\n| rowspan=3 {{Party shading/Democratic}} | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| rowspan=3 nowrap | January 3, 1993 \u2013<br/>Present\n| rowspan=3 | {{USCongressOrdinal|103|Present}}\n| rowspan=3 nowrap | [[1992 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Elected in 1992]].<br/>[[1994 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1994]].<br/>[[1996 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1996]].<br/>[[1998 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 1998]].<br/>[[2000 Illinois's 1st congressional district election|Re-elected in 2000]].<br/>[[2002 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2002]].<br/>[[2004 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2004]].<br/>[[2006 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2006]].<br/>[[2008 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2008]].<br/>[[2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2010]].<br/>[[2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2012]].<br/>[[2014 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2014]].<br/>[[2016 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2016]].<br/>[[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois|Re-elected in 2018]].\n| '''1993 \u2013 2003'''<br/>{{Small|Expanded into the suburbs for the first time in 90 years, increasing its total area from 32 to {{convert|56|sqmi|km2}}. It now included: the Chicago communities of [[Douglas, Chicago|Douglas]], [[Oakland, Chicago|Oakland]], [[Kenwood, Chicago|Kenwood]], [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]], [[Woodlawn, Chicago|Woodlawn]], [[Greater Grand Crossing, Chicago|Greater Grand Crossing]], [[Avalon Park, Chicago|Avalon Park]], [[Burnside, Chicago|Burnside]], [[Chatham, Chicago|Chatham]] and [[Mount Greenwood, Chicago|Mount Greenwood]]; those portions of [[Auburn Gresham, Chicago|Auburn Gresham]] and [[Washington Heights, Chicago|Washington Heights]] east of Halsted, those portions of [[Roseland, Chicago|Roseland]] and [[Pullman, Chicago|Pullman]] north of 103rd Street, and those portions of [[Calumet Heights, Chicago|Calumet Heights]] and [[South Chicago, Chicago|South Chicago]] west of Yates Boulevard; the portion of [[South Deering, Chicago|South Deering]] northwest of 103rd and Yates; [[South Shore, Chicago|South Shore]], excepting the area southeast of 71st and Yates; [[Washington Park, Chicago (neighborhood)|Washington Park]], excepting the area northwest of 57th and King Drive; the part of [[Grand Boulevard, Chicago|Grand Boulevard]] north of 43rd Street, as well as most of the area east of Vincennes Avenue; the portion of [[Armour Square, Chicago|Armour Square]] southeast of 35th Street and Princeton Avenue; most of [[Englewood, Chicago|Englewood]] north of 63rd or east of Halsted; the portion of [[West Englewood, Chicago|West Englewood]] north of 63rd; most of [[New City, Chicago|New City]] southwest of 49th and May Streets; most of [[Brighton Park, Chicago|Brighton Park]] southeast of 40th and Kedzie Avenue; portions of [[Gage Park, Chicago|Gage Park]] east of Kedzie, most of [[Chicago Lawn, Chicago|Chicago Lawn]] east of Kedzie, and the portion of [[Ashburn, Chicago|Ashburn]] east of Kedzie; [[Beverly, Chicago|Beverly]], excepting the area southeast of 103rd and Prospect Avenue; and most of [[Morgan Park, Chicago|Morgan Park]] west of Vincennes. In the suburbs, the district included the villages of [[Evergreen Park, Illinois|Evergreen Park]] and [[Merrionette Park, Illinois|Merrionette Park]], the portion of [[Alsip, Illinois|Alsip]] east of Cicero Avenue, the portion of [[Blue Island, Illinois|Blue Island]] in Worth Township north of the [[Calumet River#Cal-Sag Channel|Calumet Sag Channel]], and, with minor variations, the portion of [[Oak Lawn, Illinois|Oak Lawn]] southeast of 101st and Cicero.<ref>{{cite book | title=Congressional District Atlas: 103rd Congress of the United States | year=1993 | publisher=U.S. Bureau of the Census | location=Washington, D.C. | isbn=0-16-041689-2 | pages=Illinois-1, 5, 25, 28\u201333 }}</ref>}}\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| '''2003 \u2013 2013'''<br/>[[File:IL01 109.gif|300px]]\n\n|- style=\"height:3em\"\n| '''2013 \u2013 Present'''<br/>{{Small|See map and [[#Geography|geography]] above. For a more detailed map, see the Census Bureau map [[#External links|linked below]].}}\n\n|}\n\n==Election results==\n\n===2002===\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Illinois's 1st Congressional District Election (2002)}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  | party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  | candidate  = [[Bobby Rush]]*\n  | votes      = 149,068\n  | percentage = 81.17\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  | party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  | candidate  = Raymond G. Wardingley\n  | votes      = 29,776\n  | percentage = 16.21\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  | party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  | candidate  = Dorothy Tsatsos\n  | votes      = 4,812\n  | percentage = 2.62\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n  | votes      = 183,656\n  | percentage = 100.00\n}}\n{{Election box turnout no change\n  | percentage =\n}}\n{{Election 