{"title_page": "Aster Medcity", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Aster Medcity\n| Org/Group  = [[Aster DM Healthcare]]\n| Image      = Aster Medcity Hospital Entrance.jpg\n| Caption    = Hospital complex\n| Logo       = Logo_of_Aster_Medcity.png\n| coordinates = {{coord|10|02|36.4|N|76|16|41.0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| Location   = [[Cheranallur]], [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]]\n| Country    = India\n| HealthCare = [[Quaternary]]\n| Type       = \n| Speciality = \n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Affiliation=  \n| Beds       = 670\n| Founded    = 6 May 2015\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{Website|http://astermedcity.com|Official Website}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Aster Medcity''' is a [[quaternary care]] healthcare centre in the city of [[Kochi]] and one of the largest in [[South India]].<ref name=\"Aster Medcity Hospital in Kochi \u2013 in pictures\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/economy/aster-medcity-hospital-in-kochi--in-pictures#1 | title=Aster Medcity Hospital in Kochi \u2013 in pictures | publisher=The National | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> It is the flagship hospital of [[Aster DM Healthcare]], a healthcare conglomerate founded by [[Azad Moopen]].<ref name=\"Aster DM Healthcare\">{{cite web | url=http://asterdmhealthcare.com/ | title=Aster DM Healthcare | publisher=Aster DM Healthcare | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> This was the third venture of the group in Kerala, after the [[Malabar Institute of Medical Sciences]] (MIMS) and DM Wayanad Institute of Medical Sciences (DMWIMS).<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\">{{cite web|url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/f50e70b3-99fe-4573-bd22-5c59fec29f58.aspx |title=Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala |publisher=Gulf Today |date=7 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705121753/http://gulftoday.ae/portal/f50e70b3-99fe-4573-bd22-5c59fec29f58.aspx |archivedate=5 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Aster Medcity Front lobby.jpg|left|thumb|Main Reception]]\nAster Medcity is a {{INR}} 5.5 billion waterfront facility<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/mobile/inside.asp?xfile=/data/international/2014/November/international_November202.xml&section=international | title=Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients | publisher=Khaleej Times | date=10 November 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> located along Kutti Sahib Road in [[Cheranallur]], a [[suburb]] of [[Kochi]] and its 40-acre campus is situated on the banks of the [[Kerala backwaters|backwaters]] of Kochi.<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital complex, designed by HKS Architects, has a built up space measuring a total of 62,710 square metres.<ref name=\"HKS Architects\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hksinc.com/places/dm-healthcare-aster-medcity/ | title=HKS Architects | publisher=HKS Architects | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> The hospital is 7&nbsp;km from the city center and is accessible through the [[National Highway 66 (India)]]. [[Edappally railway station]] is 7.3&nbsp;km away and the nearest airport is [[Kochi International Airport]], 24.7&nbsp;km from the hospital by road. The distance to the [[National Highway 544]] is 7.9&nbsp;km at [[Edappally Junction|Edappally bye-pass junction]] where [[LuLu International Shopping Mall|Lulu Mall]], the largest shopping mall in the country, is located.\n\nThe hospital has an in-patient capacity of 670 beds and has 24 hour emergency and accident trauma care facilities.<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital has been functioning since September 2014 after a soft launch but the official dedication ceremony was on 6 May 2015, when the institution was inaugurated by the former president of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]].<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital plans to add 500 more beds in its second phase of expansion.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" />\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Laproscopic Surgery Robot.jpg|left|thumb|[[da Vinci Surgical System]].]]\nThe hospital has a general clinical division which includes Internal medicine, General surgery, Cilinical imaging, Anesthesia and critical care, Emergency, Pulmonology, otorhynolaryngology, Dermatology, Craniomaxillofacial surgery, Dental sciences, Infectious diseases and infection control, Psychiatry and Nuclear medicine. It also has eight centres of excellence such as Cardiac Sciences, Orthopedics, Neurosciences, Nephrology and Urology, Oncology, Gastroenterology and Hepatology, Women's Health and Child and Adolescent Health, each manned by independent medical teams composed of specialists, nursing and ancillary staff and technicians.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" />\n\nAster Medcity has facility for Minimal Access Robotic Surgery (MARS) using [[da Vinci Surgical System]]<ref name=\"60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi\">{{cite web | url=http://www.me-newswire.net/news/60-robotic-surgeries-in-a-span-of-6-months-a-milestone-at-aster-medcity-kochi/en | title=60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi | publisher=Middle East News | date=31 March 2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> and is reported to be the first hospital in Kerala to provide the service.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" /> The system employs telesurgical master-slave robotic system and the surgery is carried out using robotic arms instead of human hands.<ref name=\"60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi\" /> The Diagnostics division is equipped with 3 Tesla Digital [[MRI Scanner]], 256 slice [[CT Scanner]], Digital [[Mammography]] system, The Dexa, Digital X-Ray, Time of Flight PET CT, Cath Lab Allura Clarity system, Flat panel Bi-plane Hybrid Cath Lab, Colour Doppler Systems electronic 4D Imaging and Ultrasound Machines with multi modal image fusion. The clinical laboratory which conducts Biochemistry, Haematology, Bacteriology, Mycology, BS Level 3 Tuberculosis, Serology, Immunology, Histopathology, Neuropathology, Renal pathology, Pulmonary pathology, Haematopathology, Bone Pathology and Onco pathology tests, is integrated with the hospital information system. The hospital has an ambulance service, a pharmacy and a rehabilitation centre. A blood bank is also operational round the clock.\n\n==Other services==\nAster Medcity is linked to Aster Foundation, an independent charitable [[non governmental organization]], engaged in providing free medical assistance to financially compromised patients.<ref name=\"Dr. Moopen's Foundation initiative helps Dubai-based Filipino boy get a new lease of life\">{{cite web|url=http://www.godubai.com/citylife/print.asp?pr=91021 |title=Dr. Moopen's Foundation initiative helps Dubai-based Filipino boy get a new lease of life |publisher=GoDubai |date=2015 |accessdate=4 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705180241/http://www.godubai.com/citylife/print.asp?pr=91021 |archivedate=5 July 2015 }}</ref> The hospital serves as a referral healthcare centre for patients from the [[Persian Gulf]] region. The group has opened help desks in Qatar<ref name=\"Aster Medcity, south Asia\u2019s largest quaternary care hospital, sets up a helpdesk in Qatar\">{{cite web | url=http://ameinfo.com/finance-and-economy/economy/healthcare/aster-medcity-south-asias-largest-quaternary-care-hospital-sets-helpdesk-qatar/ | title=Aster Medcity, south Asia\u2019s largest quaternary care hospital, sets up a helpdesk in Qatar | publisher=AME Info | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> and Oman<ref name=\"Aster DM Healthcare to Start Helpdesks in Oman\">{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-367098294.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154826/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-367098294.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=24 September 2015 | title=Aster DM Healthcare to Start Helpdesks in Oman | publisher=High Beam | date=24 April 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> for this purpose.\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Malabar Institute of Medical Sciences]]\n* [[Aster DM Healthcare]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aster Medcity}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H3ZOOzCXI7M | title=Aster Medcity | publisher=Lensman Moviemakers | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=1 August 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://kumganghealthcare.com/hospitals/dm-aster-in-cochin.html | title=DM Aster Hospital | publisher=K Healthcare | date=2015 | accessdate=9 September 2015}}\n\n\n{{Health in Kerala |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Kochi]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 2015]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Aster Medcity\n| Org/Group  = [[Aster DM Healthcare]]\n| Image      = Aster Medcity Hospital Entrance.jpg\n| Caption    = Hospital complex\n| Logo       = Logo_of_Aster_Medcity.png\n| coordinates = {{coord|10|02|36.4|N|76|16|41.0|E|display=inline,title}}\n| Location   = [[Cheranallur]], [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]]\n| Country    = India\n| HealthCare = [[Quaternary]]\n| Type       = \n| Speciality = \n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Affiliation=  \n| Beds       = 670\n| Founded    = 6 May 2015\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{Website|http://astermedcity.com|Official Website}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Aster Medcity''' is a [[quaternary care]] healthcare centre in the city of [[Kochi]] and one of the largest in [[South India]].<ref name=\"Aster Medcity Hospital in Kochi \u2013 in pictures\">{{cite web | url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/economy/aster-medcity-hospital-in-kochi--in-pictures#1 | title=Aster Medcity Hospital in Kochi \u2013 in pictures | publisher=The National | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> It is the flagship hospital of [[Aster DM Healthcare]], a healthcare conglomerate founded by [[Azad Moopen]].<ref name=\"Aster DM Healthcare\">{{cite web | url=http://asterdmhealthcare.com/ | title=Aster DM Healthcare | publisher=Aster DM Healthcare | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> This was the third venture of the group in Kerala, after the [[Malabar Institute of Medical Sciences]] (MIMS) and DM Wayanad Institute of Medical Sciences (DMWIMS).<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\">{{cite web|url=http://gulftoday.ae/portal/f50e70b3-99fe-4573-bd22-5c59fec29f58.aspx |title=Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala |publisher=Gulf Today |date=7 May 2015 |accessdate=4 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705121753/http://gulftoday.ae/portal/f50e70b3-99fe-4573-bd22-5c59fec29f58.aspx |archivedate=5 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Aster Medcity Front lobby.jpg|left|thumb|Main Reception]]\nAster Medcity is a {{INR}} 5.5 billion waterfront facility<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/mobile/inside.asp?xfile=/data/international/2014/November/international_November202.xml&section=international | title=Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients | publisher=Khaleej Times | date=10 November 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> located along Kutti Sahib Road in [[Cheranallur]], a [[suburb]] of [[Kochi]] and its 40-acre campus is situated on the banks of the [[Kerala backwaters|backwaters]] of Kochi.<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital complex, designed by HKS Architects, has a built up space measuring a total of 62,710 square metres.<ref name=\"HKS Architects\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hksinc.com/places/dm-healthcare-aster-medcity/ | title=HKS Architects | publisher=HKS Architects | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> The hospital is 7&nbsp;km from the city center and is accessible through the [[National Highway NH66]]. [[Edappally railway station]] is 7.3&nbsp;km away via NH66 and the nearest airport is [[Kochi International Airport]], 24.7&nbsp;km from the hospital by road. The distance to the [[National Highway 544]] is 7.9&nbsp;km at [[Edappally Junction|Edappally bye-pass junction]] where [[LuLu International Shopping Mall|Lulu Mall]], the largest shopping mall in the country, is located.\n\nThe hospital has an in-patient capacity of 670 beds and has 24 hour emergency and accident trauma care facilities.<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital has been functioning since September 2014 after a soft launch but the official dedication ceremony was on 6 May 2015, when the institution was inaugurated by the former president of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]].<ref name=\"Kalam opens Aster Medcity in Kerala\" /> The hospital plans to add 500 more beds in its second phase of expansion.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" />\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Laproscopic Surgery Robot.jpg|left|thumb|[[da Vinci Surgical System]].]]\nThe hospital has a general clinical division which includes Internal medicine, General surgery, Cilinical imaging, Anesthesia and critical care, Emergency, Pulmonology, otorhynolaryngology, Dermatology, Craniomaxillofacial surgery, Dental sciences, Infectious diseases and infection control, Psychiatry and Nuclear medicine. It also has eight centres of excellence such as Cardiac Sciences, Orthopedics, Neurosciences, Nephrology and Urology, Oncology, Gastroenterology and Hepatology, Women's Health and Child and Adolescent Health, each manned by independent medical teams composed of specialists, nursing and ancillary staff and technicians.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" />\n\nAster Medcity has facility for Minimal Access Robotic Surgery (MARS) using [[da Vinci Surgical System]]<ref name=\"60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi\">{{cite web | url=http://www.me-newswire.net/news/60-robotic-surgeries-in-a-span-of-6-months-a-milestone-at-aster-medcity-kochi/en | title=60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi | publisher=Middle East News | date=31 March 2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> and is reported to be the first hospital in Kerala to provide the service.<ref name=\"Medcity \u2014 A big relief for advanced stage patients\" /> The system employs telesurgical master-slave robotic system and the surgery is carried out using robotic arms instead of human hands.<ref name=\"60 Robotic Surgeries in a Span of 6 months: a Milestone at Aster Medcity-Kochi\" /> The Diagnostics division is equipped with 3 Tesla Digital [[MRI Scanner]], 256 slice [[CT Scanner]], Digital [[Mammography]] system, The Dexa, Digital X-Ray, Time of Flight PET CT, Cath Lab Allura Clarity system, Flat panel Bi-plane Hybrid Cath Lab, Colour Doppler Systems electronic 4D Imaging and Ultrasound Machines with multi modal image fusion. The clinical laboratory which conducts Biochemistry, Haematology, Bacteriology, Mycology, BS Level 3 Tuberculosis, Serology, Immunology, Histopathology, Neuropathology, Renal pathology, Pulmonary pathology, Haematopathology, Bone Pathology and Onco pathology tests, is integrated with the hospital information system. The hospital has an ambulance service, a pharmacy and a rehabilitation centre. A blood bank is also operational round the clock.\n\n==Other services==\nAster Medcity is linked to Aster Foundation, an independent charitable [[non governmental organization]], engaged in providing free medical assistance to financially compromised patients.<ref name=\"Dr. Moopen's Foundation initiative helps Dubai-based Filipino boy get a new lease of life\">{{cite web|url=http://www.godubai.com/citylife/print.asp?pr=91021 |title=Dr. Moopen's Foundation initiative helps Dubai-based Filipino boy get a new lease of life |publisher=GoDubai |date=2015 |accessdate=4 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705180241/http://www.godubai.com/citylife/print.asp?pr=91021 |archivedate=5 July 2015 }}</ref> The hospital serves as a referral healthcare centre for patients from the [[Persian Gulf]] region. The group has opened help desks in Qatar<ref name=\"Aster Medcity, south Asia\u2019s largest quaternary care hospital, sets up a helpdesk in Qatar\">{{cite web | url=http://ameinfo.com/finance-and-economy/economy/healthcare/aster-medcity-south-asias-largest-quaternary-care-hospital-sets-helpdesk-qatar/ | title=Aster Medcity, south Asia\u2019s largest quaternary care hospital, sets up a helpdesk in Qatar | publisher=AME Info | date=2015 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> and Oman<ref name=\"Aster DM Healthcare to Start Helpdesks in Oman\">{{cite web | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-367098294.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154826/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-367098294.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=24 September 2015 | title=Aster DM Healthcare to Start Helpdesks in Oman | publisher=High Beam | date=24 April 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}</ref> for this purpose.\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Malabar Institute of Medical Sciences]]\n* [[Aster DM Healthcare]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Aster Medcity}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H3ZOOzCXI7M | title=Aster Medcity | publisher=Lensman Moviemakers | work=[[YouTube]] video | date=1 August 2014 | accessdate=4 July 2015}}\n* {{cite web | url=http://kumganghealthcare.com/hospitals/dm-aster-in-cochin.html | title=DM Aster Hospital | publisher=K Healthcare | date=2015 | accessdate=9 September 2015}}\n\n\n{{Health in Kerala |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2015 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Kochi]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 2015]]\n", "name_user": "Xxx.12AD", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aster_Medcity"}
{"title_page": "Tarlaba\u015f\u0131", "text_new": "{{short description|Neighborhood in Istanbul, Turkey}}\n<!--This article is in Commonwealth English-->\n[[Image:Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Cad \u0130stanbul.JPG|thumb|right|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Boulevard]]\n'''Tarlaba\u015f\u0131''' is a neighbourhood in the [[Beyo\u011flu]] district in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]] stretching from [[Taksim Square]] and [[Talimhane]] in the north to {{ill|Tepeba\u015f\u0131, Beyo\u011flu|lt=Tepeba\u015f\u0131|tr}} in the south. It is bordered on the east side by the four-lane Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Bulvar\u0131 and by Dolapdere Caddesi on the west.\n\nOn Tatl\u0131 Badem (\"Sweet Almond') Street, there is a museum dedicated to the Polish poet [[Adam Mickiewicz]] who died here of cholera in 1855. His body in 1855 was transported to France (Montmorency) and then - in 1890 - to Poland (Cracow), where he was finally buried. Currently the museum is closed.   \n\nOn Sundays, the neighborhood hosts a popular bazaar with hundreds of vendors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culinarybackstreets.com/cities-category/istanbul/2018/market-watch-4/|title=Market Watch: Semt Pazarlar\u0131, Civic Life Perfected|date=2018-03-09|website=Culinary Backstreets|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe neighborhood is primarily low-income, and it has been called \"Istanbul's oldest slum.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/jun/02/syrias-gypsy-refugees-sanctuary-istanbul-turkey-ghetto-how-long-will-last|title=Syria's most hated refugees find sanctuary in an Istanbul ghetto|last=Cox|first=David|date=2016-06-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> However, it is also a historic and diverse community, which is known for its [[Kurds|Kurdish]], [[Syrian Refugees|Syrian Refugee]]<ref name=\":0\" />[[Syrians|,]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] communities. In the 1990s, large numbers of [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] immigrants from southeastern Turkey moved into Tarlaba\u015f\u0131, mixing in with the local [[Romani people|Romani]] population. More recently, it has become the home to many migrants from neighbouring countries and [[Africa]].<ref>[https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2017/03/11/arafta-kalmis-bir-tukenis-hikayesiydi-tarlabasi/ Arafta kalm\u0131\u015f bir t\u00fckeni\u015f hik\u00e2yesiydi Tarlaba\u015f\u0131]</ref> The neighborhood is home to a sizable [[transgender]] community as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenintheworld.com/2017/04/20/an-unflinching-look-inside-the-most-dangerous-place-in-europe-to-be-a-transgender-person/|title=An unflinching look inside the most dangerous place in Europe to be a transgender person|date=2017-04-20|website=Women in the World|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2016-12-16/people-are-risking-their-lives-trans-istanbul</ref>\n\nThere have been threats to the local community, as the government is interested in \"regeneration\" projects, which may displace poor residents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/05/world/middleeast/05iht-m05-turkey-tarlabasi.html|title=Poor but Proud Istanbul Neighborhood Faces Gentrification|last=Bourque|first=Jessica|date=2012-07-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 is about 20,000 square metres, consisting of 9 blocks and 278 plots, in Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 were declared a regeneration area by the government in February 2006 following a petition from the local municipality. The recently released renewal law for the Protection of Deteriorated Historic and Cultural Heritage through Renewal and Re-use, forms the basis of the renewal process in Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 as well as in many other neighbourhoods within the historic city.<ref>[http://www.urban-age.net/publications/newspapers/istanbul/articles/14_TolgaIslam/en_GB/ Tarlaba\u015f\u0131]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2658.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2666.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2683.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2678.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2676.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2668.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20121128191619/http://216.35.221.77/templates/story/story.php?storyId=11965693 Istanbul's Tarlabasi Under Constant Transformation]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Turkey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarlabasi}}\n[[Category:Beyo\u011flu]]\n[[Category:Quarters in Istanbul]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Neighborhood in Istanbul, Turkey}}\n<!--This article is in Commonwealth English-->\n[[Image:Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Cad \u0130stanbul.JPG|thumb|right|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Boulevard]]\n'''Tarlaba\u015f\u0131''' is a neighbourhood in the [[Beyo\u011flu]] district in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]] stretching from [[Taksim Square]] and [[Talimhane]] in the north to {{ill|Tepeba\u015f\u0131, Beyo\u011flu|lt=Tepeba\u015f\u0131|tr}} in the south. It is bordered on the east side by the four-lane Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Bulvar\u0131 and by Dolapdere Caddesi on the west.\n\nOn Tatl\u0131 Badem (\"Sweet Almond') Street, there is a museum dedicated to the Polish poet [[Adam Mickiewicz]] who died here of cholera in 1855. His body in 1855 was transported to France (Montmorency) and then - in 1890 - to Poland (Cracow), where he was finally buried. \n\nOn Sundays, the neighborhood hosts a popular bazaar with hundreds of vendors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://culinarybackstreets.com/cities-category/istanbul/2018/market-watch-4/|title=Market Watch: Semt Pazarlar\u0131, Civic Life Perfected|date=2018-03-09|website=Culinary Backstreets|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref>\n\nThe neighborhood is primarily low-income, and it has been called \"Istanbul's oldest slum.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2016/jun/02/syrias-gypsy-refugees-sanctuary-istanbul-turkey-ghetto-how-long-will-last|title=Syria's most hated refugees find sanctuary in an Istanbul ghetto|last=Cox|first=David|date=2016-06-02|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> However, it is also a historic and diverse community, which is known for its [[Kurds|Kurdish]], [[Syrian Refugees|Syrian Refugee]]<ref name=\":0\" />[[Syrians|,]] and [[Romani people|Romani]] communities. In the 1990s, large numbers of [[Kurdish People|Kurdish]] immigrants from southeastern Turkey moved into Tarlaba\u015f\u0131, mixing in with the local [[Romani people|Romani]] population. More recently, it has become the home to many migrants from neighbouring countries and [[Africa]].<ref>[https://yesilgazete.org/blog/2017/03/11/arafta-kalmis-bir-tukenis-hikayesiydi-tarlabasi/ Arafta kalm\u0131\u015f bir t\u00fckeni\u015f hik\u00e2yesiydi Tarlaba\u015f\u0131]</ref> The neighborhood is home to a sizable [[transgender]] community as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenintheworld.com/2017/04/20/an-unflinching-look-inside-the-most-dangerous-place-in-europe-to-be-a-transgender-person/|title=An unflinching look inside the most dangerous place in Europe to be a transgender person|date=2017-04-20|website=Women in the World|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-18}}</ref><ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2016-12-16/people-are-risking-their-lives-trans-istanbul</ref>\n\nThere have been threats to the local community, as the government is interested in \"regeneration\" projects, which may displace poor residents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/05/world/middleeast/05iht-m05-turkey-tarlabasi.html|title=Poor but Proud Istanbul Neighborhood Faces Gentrification|last=Bourque|first=Jessica|date=2012-07-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 is about 20,000 square metres, consisting of 9 blocks and 278 plots, in Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 were declared a regeneration area by the government in February 2006 following a petition from the local municipality. The recently released renewal law for the Protection of Deteriorated Historic and Cultural Heritage through Renewal and Re-use, forms the basis of the renewal process in Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 as well as in many other neighbourhoods within the historic city.<ref>[http://www.urban-age.net/publications/newspapers/istanbul/articles/14_TolgaIslam/en_GB/ Tarlaba\u015f\u0131]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2658.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2666.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2683.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2678.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2676.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\nFile:Tarlabashi Mahallesi 2668.jpg|Tarlaba\u015f\u0131 Building\n</gallery>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20121128191619/http://216.35.221.77/templates/story/story.php?storyId=11965693 Istanbul's Tarlabasi Under Constant Transformation]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Turkey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tarlabasi}}\n[[Category:Beyo\u011flu]]\n[[Category:Quarters in Istanbul]]\n", "name_user": "Sasha Cheese", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add info about the museum that is currently closed in this area", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarlaba%C5%9F%C4%B1"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Whiteside", "text_new": "{{for|the major who participated in the [[Wounded Knee Massacre]]|Samuel Whitside}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Samuel A. Whiteside\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Whiteside photo.jpg\n| state_delegate = Illinois\n| district = \n| term_start = 1819\n| term_end = 1821\n| preceded = \n| succeeded =\n| birth_date ={{birth date|1783|4|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Rutherford County, North Carolina|Rutherford County]], [[North Carolina]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1866|1|12|1783|4|12|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Christian County, Illinois]]\n| party =\n| spouse =Nancy Miller\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| profession = Farmer, soldier, politician\n| committees =\n| allegiance ={{flag|United States of America|name=United States}}\n| branch = U.S. Army, Ranger\n| serviceyears = 1810-1814; 1831\u20131832\n| rank =captain (1812-1814)<br>general (1811-1812), (1831-1832)<br>corporal(1832\u20131833)\n| unit = Illinois militia\n| commands =[[Blackhawk War]]\n| battles =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Whiteside''' (April 12, 1783 \u2013 January 12, 1866) was an [[Illinois]] pioneer. A farmer and backwoodsman, Whiteside briefly served in the [[Illinois General Assembly]] after statehood and led the Illinois militia for decades, rising to the rank of general but also enlisting as an ordinary soldier when militia calls declined at the end of wars. Whiteside fought the British in the [[War of 1812]] and Native Americans through the [[Blackhawk War]] (including in the [[Illinois Territory]] before statehood and later in the [[Wisconsin Territory]]).<ref>[http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html Samuel Whiteside]</ref>\n\n==Early and family life==\nSamuel Whiteside was born on April 12, 1783, in [[Rutherford County, North Carolina]] to the former Judith Tolley and her husband John D. Whiteside. His paternal grandfather, William Whiteside Sr., was a patriot who signed the [[Tryon Resolves]] during the  [[American Revolutionary War]], and whose sons Davis, James, John D., William B., Thomas, Samuel, and Adam Whiteside all fought the British at the [[Battle of Kings Mountain]] in 1780. Davis Whiteside died of wounds suffered in that battle, previously having also signed the [[Tryon Resolves]].<ref>\n[http://members.tripod.com/mmkasik/id23.htm Whiteside family signers of the Tryon Resolves]</ref><ref>\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20071231165043/http://www.dar.org/natsociety/pi.cfm Daughters of the American Revolution Patriot Index]</ref><ref>[http://mmkasik.tribalpages.com/tribe/browse?userid=mmkasik&view=0&rand=867481703&pid=68 Great granddaughter's genealogy website]</ref>\n\nAround 1792, Whiteside and his remaining sons moved west toward [[St. Louis, Missouri]], to take advantage of land claims allotted to veterans. Before crossing the [[Mississippi River]], they settled near [[Columbia, Illinois|Columbia]], [[Monroe County, Illinois]] on the abandoned Flannery Fort site protecting the important early [[Kaskaskia]] to [[Cahokia]] Trail. Flannery had been killed and scalped during an attack by Native Americans in 1783 and the site had been abandoned for a decade.<ref>https://madison-historical.siue.edu/encyclopedia/william-bolin-whiteside-1777-1833/</ref> The elder William F. Whiteside was a militia captain and lived at the fort, which was called Whiteside Station until he died in 1815 (shortly before Illinois became a state). He had survived his son Thomas (who died at the fort in 1795, possibly during the Indian raid that Samuel survived and which shaped his later military career).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref>\n\nHis son John (Samuel's father) moved his family to Bellefountaine (now [[Waterloo, Illinois]]), also on the Kaskaskia/Cahokia trail in [[Monroe County, Illinois]]; his nephew another John D. Whiteside (1799-1850) would later represent Monroe County in the Illinois legislature.<ref>http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/whitehurst-whiticar.html#RNS0UMLUB</ref> Around 1800 many Whiteside descendants moved to the [[Goshen Settlement]], in [[Madison County, Illinois]], about 12 miles northeast of St. Louis and near modern [[Edwardsville, Illinois]]. One of them was William Bolin Whiteside (1777-1833), who owned at least two slaves, became a militia captain for that area for decades and was elected the first sheriff of Madison County after statehood (and served until a scandal in 1822).<ref>https://madison-historical.siue.edu/encyclopedia/william-bolin-whiteside-1777-1833/</ref> Meanwhile, this Samuel Whiteside and his brother Joel purchased land in what became [[Maryville, Illinois]] (in Madison County about 17 miles from St. Louis) in 1802.<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> Some Whiteside relatives would cross the Mississippi River and [[Whiteside, Missouri]] would be named after early landowner William Whiteside. Other Whitesides (including this Samuel's children) moved inland to [[Niantic, Illinois|Niantic]], [[Macon County, Illinois]].\nMeanwhile, Samuel Whiteside in 1804 married Virginia-born Nancy Miller (1789-1851). Their children included: Michael Whiteside (1805-1881), Judith Whiteside Waddell (1806-1876), Nancy Whiteside (b. 1808), Sarah Whiteside (b. 1810), Joel Whiteside (1811-1882), William Modrel Whiteside (1812-1864), Thomas Whiteside (b.1815), Samuel Ray Whiteside (1820-1866), Elizabeth Ann (Eliza) Whiteside Henderson (1812-1910), John Perry Whiteside (1822-) and Mary Ann Whiteside (b. 1830).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> The family did not own slaves in the 1820 Federal census, nor the 1830 Federal census. In the 1850 census, Samuel Whiteside farmed in Madison County near his younger sons Samuel Ray and John Perry Whiteside and their families; the census found no slaves in the county.<ref>1850 U.S.Federal Census for Township 3 North R8 West, Madison County, Illinois, family 99 (p. 11 of 21); ancestry.com indicates the county has no slave schedules for that census</ref>\n\n==Indian fighter, legislator and farmer==\nIn 1811, during [[Tecumseh's War]], Whiteside (tho not yet 20 years old) received command of a company, in the newly formed 17th Illinois Infantry. The following year, during the [[War of 1812]], Captain Samuel Whiteside commanded a company of mounted infantry in the Illinois militia from August to November 1812. This company was drawn from [[St. Clair County, Illinois|St. Clair County]], which adjoined Columbia, Illinois to the north and comprised most of the modern State. Whiteside had enlisted as an ensign (January 2, 1810) in the Illinois militia and received promotions to captain (August 22, 1812), major (February 26, 1817), colonel (May 22, 1817) and brigadier general (1819).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> Once during the War of 1812, captain Whiteside saved boats of fellow soldiers who tried to cross the Mississippi to attack St. Louis, but were endangered during a retreat by shifting winds as well as the great river's current.<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref>\n\nIn August 1813 Whiteside received a captain's commission in the [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] and led a [[United States Army Rangers|Ranger]] unit. In 1814, a woman and six children near [[Alton, Illinois]] were killed by [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]. Captain Whiteside and his men pursued the killers, and killed one of them found hiding in a tree. Whiteside was discharged from the Army on July 30, 1814, but was among the witnesses to treaties with the [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]] and [[Osage Nation|Osage]] in 1815.<ref>Louis Houck, History of Missouri (Chicago, RR Donnelly & Sons), Vol. 2 Ch. 22 (1908) p. 398</ref>\n\nFollowing Illinois' statehood in 1818, Whiteside served on the commission to select a new site for the Illinois State Capital, selecting [[Vandalia, Illinois]] at the confluence of the [[Kaskaskia River|Kaskaskia]] and Mississippi Rivers and the end of the [[National Road]]; it would remain the state capital until Abraham Lincoln and other legislators secured a move inland to [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] in 1839. Meanwhile, voters elected Whiteside as a delegate in the first [[Illinois General Assembly]]; he served from 1819 to 1821 and did not seek re-election. Instead, he returned to farming and leading the Madison County militia.\n\nIn 1827, after drunk boatman abducted and raped several [[Ho-Chunk]] (Winnebago) women near what became [[Prairie Du Chien, Wisconsin]] (then [[Wisconsin Territory]]) and their menfolk rescued them in a skirmish in which both Native Americans and whites died, Whiteside and his militiamen, along with Generals [[Lewis Cass]] and [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]] and Col. [[Henry Dodge]] pursued the Winnebago warriors. Chief [[Red Bird]] surrendered at [[Portage, Wisconsin|Portage]] on the condition that his people would suffer no reprisals, but died in prison a year later.<ref>\"Winnebago uprising\" in url=https://online.infobase.com/Auth/Index?aid=96330&itemid=WE52&articleId=209191</ref>\n\nFrom April 26 to June 30, 1832 during the [[Black Hawk War]], Governor [[John Reynolds (Illinois politician)|John Reynolds]] commissioned Whiteside as a brigadier general in the Illinois militia. Whiteside in turn commissioned 23-year-old [[Abraham Lincoln]] as a militia captain (and Lincoln would serve a month until this phase of the war ended); future governor [[Thomas Ford (politician)|Thomas Ford]] also served under Whiteside. In late April, U.S. Army General Henry Atkinson at [[Rock Island, Illinois|Rock Island]] sent Reynolds, Whiteside and their militia up the [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock River]] and the [[Sauk Trail]], planning to join forces at [[Prophetstown, Illinois]], home of [[Wabokieshiek]] (White Cloud), one of Black Hawk's chief advisors and who had created the settlement after Black Hawk had been barred from his native village [[Saukenuk]] at the confluence of the Mississippi and Rock Rivers. On May 10, 1832, Whiteside gave the order to burn the abandoned Prophetstown, and proceeded upriver to secure [[Dixon, Illinois|Dixon's ferry]], a relatively new settlement and post office where the Peoria/Galena wagon road crossed the Rock River. Although Whiteside initially remained at Dixon waiting for the regular army, at Governor Reynolds' urging, he sent a scout company under Major [[Isaiah Stillman]] to seek out Black Hawk's British Band. Stillman's men imprisoned some of Black Hawk's emissaries, but fled after the British Band attacked; General Whiteside led the small group which buried the 11 dead militiamen after what became known as the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]].<ref>\"Battle of Stillman's Run\" in William B. Kessell, Encyclopedia of Native American Wars and Warfare (2005), available online</ref> When the militia troops were discharged as the war's Rock River valley phase ended in June 1832, Whiteside volunteered to continue as a private and fought until the war's end.<ref>Thomas Ford, A History of Illinois: from its commencement as a state in 1818 to 1847 (annotated and introduced by Rodney O. Davis; University of Illinois Press 1995) pp.</ref>\n\nWhiteside again returned to farming in Madison County, Illinois. In 1854, three years after burying his wife, he sold the farm and moved inland to [[Christian County, Illinois]], where several of his children had moved. He lived with son-in-law William Henderson, his daughter, Elizabeth and their children and hired help.<ref>1860 U.S. Federal Census for Christian County, family 1690 (p. 196 of 227)</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n[[File:Whiteside Grave 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Gravesite of General Samuel Whiteside in Hunter Cemetery Christian County, Mosquito Township Illinois.]]\nBrigadier General Samuel Whiteside died at his daughter's home in Mt. Auburn in Christian County on January 3, 1866. He is buried at Hunter Cemetery, in Christian County.<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27512000/samuel-a_-whiteside</ref>\n\nDuring his lifetime, Illinois legislators created several counties along the Rock River from lands cleared for settlement during the Blackhawk War. They named the county which included Prophetstown [[Whiteside County, Illinois]] to honor this Samuel Whiteside. His sons Joel Whiteside and Samuel Whiteside would fight for the Union in different Illinois infantry units during the [[American Civil War]]. Joel received bullet wounds in both thighs during the [[Battle of Shiloh]], which ended his military career, although he and his brother both survived the war.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Baldwin, Carl R. ''Echoes of their Voices'', (1978), LC Classification 78-71849. corporal(1811\u20131812)\n*Baldwin, Carl R. ''Captains of the Wilderness: The American Revolution on the Western Frontiers'' (1986), ({{ISBN|9997484665}}) ({{ISBN|9789997484666}}).\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Black Hawk War (1832)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whiteside, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1783 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:American militia generals]]\n[[Category:People from Edwardsville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherford County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of the Black Hawk War]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the major who participated in the [[Wounded Knee Massacre]]|Samuel Whitside}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Samuel A. Whiteside\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =Whiteside photo.jpg\n| state_delegate = Illinois\n| district = \n| term_start = 1819\n| term_end = 1821\n| preceded = \n| succeeded =\n| birth_date ={{birth date|1783|4|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Rutherford County, North Carolina|Rutherford County]], [[North Carolina]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1866|1|12|1783|4|12|mf=y}}\n| death_place = [[Christian County, Illinois]]\n| party =\n| spouse =Nancy Miller\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| profession = Farmer, soldier, politician\n| committees =\n| allegiance ={{flag|United States of America|name=United States}}\n| branch = U.S. Army, Ranger\n| serviceyears = 1810-1814; 1831\u20131832\n| rank =captain (1812-1814)<br>general (1811-1812), (1831-1832)<br>corporal(1832\u20131833)\n| unit = Illinois militia\n| commands =[[Blackhawk War]]\n| battles =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Whiteside''' (April 12, 1783 \u2013 January 12, 1866) was an [[Illinois]] pioneer. A farmer and backwoodsman, Whiteside briefly served in the [[Illinois General Assembly]] after statehood and led the Illinois militia for decades, rising to the rank of general but also enlisting as an ordinary soldier when militia calls declined at the end of wars. Whiteside fought the British in the [[War of 1812]] and Native Americans through the [[Blackhawk War]] (including in the [[Illinois Territory]] before statehood and later in the [[Wisconsin Territory]]).<ref>[http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html Samuel Whiteside]</ref>\n\n==Early and family life==\nSamuel Whiteside was born on April 12, 1783, in [[Rutherford County, North Carolina]] to the former Judith Tolley and her husband John D. Whiteside. His paternal grandfather, William Whiteside Sr., was a patriot who signed the [[Tryon Resolves]] during the  [[American Revolutionary War]], and whose sons Davis, James, John D., William B., Thomas, Samuel, and Adam Whiteside all fought the British at the [[Battle of Kings Mountain]] in 1780. Davis Whiteside died of wounds suffered in that battle, previously having also signed the [[Tryon Resolves]].<ref>\n[http://members.tripod.com/mmkasik/id23.htm Whiteside family signers of the Tryon Resolves]</ref><ref>\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20071231165043/http://www.dar.org/natsociety/pi.cfm Daughters of the American Revolution Patriot Index]</ref><ref>[http://mmkasik.tribalpages.com/tribe/browse?userid=mmkasik&view=0&rand=867481703&pid=68 Great granddaughter's genealogy website]</ref>\n\nAround 1792, Whiteside and his remaining sons moved west toward [[St. Louis, Missouri]], to take advantage of land claims allotted to veterans. Before crossing the [[Mississippi River]], they settled near [[Columbia, Illinois|Columbia]], [[Monroe County, Illinois]] on the abandoned Flannery Fort site protecting the important early [[Kaskaskia]] to [[Cahokia]] Trail. Flannery had been killed and scalped during an attack by Native Americans in 1783 and the site had been abandoned for a decade.<ref>https://madison-historical.siue.edu/encyclopedia/william-bolin-whiteside-1777-1833/</ref> The elder William F. Whiteside was a militia captain and lived at the fort, which was called Whiteside Station until he died in 1815 (shortly before Illinois became a state). He had survived his son Thomas (who died at the fort in 1795, possibly during the Indian raid that Samuel survived and which shaped his later military career).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref>\n\nHis son John (Samuel's father) moved his family to Bellefountaine (now [[Waterloo, Illinois]]), also on the Kaskaskia/Cahokia trail in [[Monroe County, Illinois]]; his nephew another John D. Whiteside (1799-1850) would later represent Monroe County in the Illinois legislature.<ref>http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/whitehurst-whiticar.html#RNS0UMLUB</ref> Around 1800 many Whiteside descendants moved to the [[Goshen Settlement]], in [[Madison County, Illinois]], about 12 miles northeast of St. Louis and near modern [[Edwardsville, Illinois]]. One of them was William Bolin Whiteside (1777-1833), who owned at least two slaves, became a militia captain for that area for decades and was elected the first sheriff of Madison County after statehood (and served until a scandal in 1822).<ref>https://madison-historical.siue.edu/encyclopedia/william-bolin-whiteside-1777-1833/</ref> Meanwhile, this Samuel Whiteside and his brother Joel purchased land in what became [[Maryville, Illinois]] (in Madison County about 17 miles from St. Louis) in 1802.<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> Some Whiteside relatives would cross the Mississippi River and [[Whiteside, Missouri]] would be named after early landowner William Whiteside. Other Whitesides (including this Samuel's children) moved inland to [[Niantic, Illinois|Niantic]], [[Macon County, Illinois]].\nMeanwhile, Samuel Whiteside in 1804 married Virginia-born Nancy Miller (1789-1851). Their children included: Michael Whiteside (1805-1881), Judith Whiteside Waddell (1806-1876), Nancy Whiteside (b. 1808), Sarah Whiteside (b. 1810), Joel Whiteside (1811-1882), William Modrel Whiteside (1812-1864), Thomas Whiteside (b.1815), Samuel Ray Whiteside (1820-1866), Elizabeth Ann (Eliza) Whiteside Henderson (1812-1910), John Perry Whiteside (1822-) and Mary Ann Whiteside (b. 1830).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> The family did not own slaves in the 1820 Federal census, nor the 1830 Federal census. In the 1850 census, Samuel Whiteside farmed in Madison County near his younger sons Samuel Ray and John Perry Whiteside and their families; the census found no slaves in the county.<ref>1850 U.S.Federal Census for Township 3 North R8 West, Madison County, Illinois, family 99 (p. 11 of 21); ancestry.com indicates the county has no slave schedules for that census</ref>\n\n==Indian fighter, legislator and farmer==\nIn 1811, during [[Tecumseh's War]], Whiteside (tho not yet 20 years old) received command of a company, in the newly formed 17th Illinois Infantry. The following year, during the [[War of 1812]], Captain Samuel Whiteside commanded a company of mounted infantry in the Illinois militia from August to November 1812. This company was drawn from [[St. Clair County, Illinois|St. Clair County]], which adjoined Columbia, Illinois to the north and comprised most of the modern State. Whiteside had enlisted as an ensign (January 2, 1810) in the Illinois militia and received promotions to captain (August 22, 1812), major (February 26, 1817), colonel (May 22, 1817) and brigadier general (1819).<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref> Once during the War of 1812, captain Whiteside saved boats of fellow soldiers who tried to cross the Mississippi to attack St. Louis, but were endangered during a retreat by shifting winds as well as the great river's current.<ref>http://illinois1812warsociety.org/samuel.html</ref>\n\nIn August 1813 Whiteside received a captain's commission in the [[Regular Army (United States)|Regular Army]] and led a [[United States Army Rangers|Ranger]] unit. In 1814, a woman and six children near [[Alton, Illinois]] were killed by [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]. Captain Whiteside and his men pursued the killers, and killed one of them found hiding in a tree. Whiteside was discharged from the Army on July 30, 1814, but was among the witnesses to treaties with the [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]] and [[Osage Nation|Osage]] in 1815.<ref>Louis Houck, History of Missouri (Chicago, RR Donnelly & Sons), Vol. 2 Ch. 22 (1908) p. 398</ref>\n\nFollowing Illinois' statehood in 1818, Whiteside served on the commission to select a new site for the Illinois State Capital, selecting [[Vandalia, Illinois]] at the confluence of the [[Kaskaskia River|Kaskaskia]] and Mississippi Rivers and the end of the [[National Road]]; it would remain the state capital until Abraham Lincoln and other legislators secured a move inland to [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] in 1839. Meanwhile, voters elected Whiteside as a delegate in the first [[Illinois General Assembly]]; he served from 1819 to 1821 and did not seek re-election. Instead, he returned to farming and leading the Madison County militia.\n\nIn 1827, after drunk boatman abducted and raped several [[Ho-Chunk]] (Winnebago) women near what became [[Prairie Du Chien, Wisconsin]] (then [[Wisconsin Territory]]) and their menfolk rescued them in a skirmish in which both Native Americans and whites died, Whiteside and his militiamen, along with Generals [[Lewis Cass]] and [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]] and Col. [[Henry Dodge]] pursued the Winnebago warriors. Chief [[Red Bird]] surrendered at [[Portage, Wisconsin|Portage]] on the condition that his people would suffer no reprisals, but died in prison a year later.<ref>\"Winnebago uprising\" in url=https://online.infobase.com/Auth/Index?aid=96330&itemid=WE52&articleId=209191</ref>\n\nFrom April 26 to June 30, 1832 during the [[Black Hawk War]], Governor [[John Reynolds (U.S. politician)|John Reynolds]] commissioned Whiteside as a brigadier general in the Illinois militia. Whiteside in turn commissioned 23-year-old [[Abraham Lincoln]] as a militia captain (and Lincoln would serve a month until this phase of the war ended); future governor [[Thomas Ford (politician)|Thomas Ford]] also served under Whiteside. In late April, U.S. Army General Henry Atkinson at [[Rock Island, Illinois|Rock Island]] sent Reynolds, Whiteside and their militia up the [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock River]] and the [[Sauk Trail]], planning to join forces at [[Prophetstown, Illinois]], home of [[Wabokieshiek]] (White Cloud), one of Black Hawk's chief advisors and who had created the settlement after Black Hawk had been barred from his native village [[Saukenuk]] at the confluence of the Mississippi and Rock Rivers. On May 10, 1832, Whiteside gave the order to burn the abandoned Prophetstown, and proceeded upriver to secure [[Dixon, Illinois|Dixon's ferry]], a relatively new settlement and post office where the Peoria/Galena wagon road crossed the Rock River. Although Whiteside initially remained at Dixon waiting for the regular army, at Governor Reynolds' urging, he sent a scout company under Major [[Isaiah Stillman]] to seek out Black Hawk's British Band. Stillman's men imprisoned some of Black Hawk's emissaries, but fled after the British Band attacked; General Whiteside led the small group which buried the 11 dead militiamen after what became known as the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]].<ref>\"Battle of Stillman's Run\" in William B. Kessell, Encyclopedia of Native American Wars and Warfare (2005), available online</ref> When the militia troops were discharged as the war's Rock River valley phase ended in June 1832, Whiteside volunteered to continue as a private and fought until the war's end.<ref>Thomas Ford, A History of Illinois: from its commencement as a state in 1818 to 1847 (annotated and introduced by Rodney O. Davis; University of Illinois Press 1995) pp.</ref>\n\nWhiteside again returned to farming in Madison County, Illinois. In 1854, three years after burying his wife, he sold the farm and moved inland to [[Christian County, Illinois]], where several of his children had moved. He lived with son-in-law William Henderson, his daughter, Elizabeth and their children and hired help.<ref>1860 U.S. Federal Census for Christian County, family 1690 (p. 196 of 227)</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n[[File:Whiteside Grave 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Gravesite of General Samuel Whiteside in Hunter Cemetery Christian County, Mosquito Township Illinois.]]\nBrigadier General Samuel Whiteside died at his daughter's home in Mt. Auburn in Christian County on January 3, 1866. He is buried at Hunter Cemetery, in Christian County.<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27512000/samuel-a_-whiteside</ref>\n\nDuring his lifetime, Illinois legislators created several counties along the Rock River from lands cleared for settlement during the Blackhawk War. They named the county which included Prophetstown [[Whiteside County, Illinois]] to honor this Samuel Whiteside. His sons Joel Whiteside and Samuel Whiteside would fight for the Union in different Illinois infantry units during the [[American Civil War]]. Joel received bullet wounds in both thighs during the [[Battle of Shiloh]], which ended his military career, although he and his brother both survived the war.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Baldwin, Carl R. ''Echoes of their Voices'', (1978), LC Classification 78-71849. corporal(1811\u20131812)\n*Baldwin, Carl R. ''Captains of the Wilderness: The American Revolution on the Western Frontiers'' (1986), ({{ISBN|9997484665}}) ({{ISBN|9789997484666}}).\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Black Hawk War (1832)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whiteside, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1783 births]]\n[[Category:1866 deaths]]\n[[Category:American militia generals]]\n[[Category:People from Edwardsville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Rutherford County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of the Black Hawk War]]\n[[Category:Members of the Illinois House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Reynolds(link changed toJohn Reynolds (Illinois politician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Whiteside"}
